\b\fs28 ONE \par
\b0\f1\fs20\par
\f0\ldblquote IF YOU\rquote LL TAKE A SEAT, sir,\rdblquote  the surgeon said, gesturing toward the chair in front of his desk. \ldblquote Please.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Thank you,\rdblquote  said Andrew Martin. \par
\tab He seated himself calmly. He did everything calmly. That was his nature; it was one part of him that would never change. Looking at him now, one could have no way of knowing that Andrew Martin had been driven to the last resort. But he had been. He had come halfway across the continent for this interview. It represented his only remaining hope of achieving his life\rquote s main goal--everything had come down to that. Everything. \par
\tab There was a smooth blankness to Andrew\rquote s face--though a keen observer might well have imagined a hint of melancholy in his eyes. His hair was smooth, light brown, rather fine, and he looked freshly and cleanly shaven: no beard, no mustache, no facial affectations of any sort. His clothes were well made and neat, predominantly a velvety red-purple \i in \i0 color; but they were of a distinctly old-fashioned cut, in the loose, flowing style called \ldblquote drapery\rdblquote  that had been popular several generations back and was rarely seen these days. \par
\tab The surgeon\rquote s face had a certain blankness about it also: hardly a surprising thing, for the surgeon\rquote s face, like all the rest of him, was fashioned of lightly bronzed stainless steel. He sat squarely upright at his imposing desk in the windowless room high over Lake Michigan, looking outward at Andrew Martin with the utmost serenity and poise evident in his glowing eyes. In front of him on the desk was a gleaming brass nameplate that announced his serial number, the usual factory-assigned assortment of letters and numbers. \par
\tab Andrew Martin paid no attention to that soulless string of characters and digits. Such dreary, mechanistic identity-designations were nothing of any moment to him--not now, not any more, not for a very long time. Andrew felt no need to call the robot surgeon anything but \ldblquote Doctor.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The surgeon said, \ldblquote This is all very irregular, you know, sir. Very irregular.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. I know that,\rdblquote  Andrew Martin said. \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve thought about very little else since this request first came to my attention.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I sincerely regret any discomfort that it may have caused you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Thank you. I am grateful for your concern.\rdblquote  \par
\tab All very formal, very courteous, very useless. They were simply fencing with each other, neither one willing to get down to essentials. And now the surgeon fell silent. Andrew waited for him to proceed. The silence went on and on. \par
\tab This is getting us nowhere, Andrew told himself. \par
\tab To the surgeon he said, \ldblquote The thing that I need to know, Doctor, is how soon the operation can be carried out.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The surgeon hesitated a perceptible moment. Then he said softly, with that certain inalienable note of respect that a robot always used when speaking to a human being, \ldblquote I am not convinced, sir, that I fully understand how such an operation could be performed, let alone why it should be considered desirable. And of course I still don\rquote t know who the subject of the proposed operation is going to be.\rdblquote  \par
\tab There might have been a look of respectful intransigence on the surgeon\rquote s face, if the elegantly contoured stainless steel of the surgeon\rquote s face had been in any way capable of displaying such an expression--or any expression at all. \par
\tab It was the turn of Andrew Martin to be silent for a moment, now. \par
\tab He studied the robot surgeon\rquote s right hand--his cutting hand--as it rested on the desk in utter tranquility. It was splendidly designed. The fingers were long and tapering, and they were shaped into metallic looping curves of great artistic beauty, curves so graceful and appropriate to their function that one could easily imagine a scalpel being fitted into them and instantly becoming, at the moment they went into action, united in perfect harmony with the fingers that wielded it: surgeon and scalpel fusing into a single marvelously capable tool. \par
\tab That was very reassuring, Andrew thought. There would be no hesitation in the surgeon\rquote s work, no stumbling, no quivering, no mistakes or even the possibility of a mistake. \par
\tab Such skill came with specialization, of course--a specialization so fiercely desired by humanity that few robots of the modern era were independently brained any more. The great majority of them nowadays were mere adjuncts of enormously powerful central processing units that had computing capacities far beyond the space limitations of a single robot frame. \par
\tab A surgeon, too, really needed to be nothing more than a set of sensors and monitors and an array of tool-manipulating devices--except that people still preferred the illusion, if nothing more than that, that they were being operated on by an individual entity, not by a limb of some remote machine. So surgeons--the ones in private practice, anyway--were still independently brained. But this one, brained or not, was so limited in his capacity that he didn\rquote t recognize Andrew Martin--had probably never heard of Andrew Martin at all, in fact. \par
\tab That was something of a novelty for Andrew. He was more than a little famous. He had never asked for his fame, of course--that was not his style--but fame, or at any rate notoriety, had come to him all the same. Because of what he had achieved: because of what he was. Not who, but \i what. \par
\tab\i0 Instead of replying to what the surgeon had asked him Andrew said, with sudden striking irrelevance, \ldblquote Tell me something, Doctor. Have you ever thought you would like to be a man?\rdblquote  \par
\tab The question, startling and strange, obviously took the surgeon aback. He hesitated a moment as though the concept of being a man was so alien to him that it would fit nowhere in his allotted positronic pathways. \par
\tab Then he recovered his aplomb and replied serenely, \ldblquote But I am a robot, sir.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Wouldn\rquote t it be better to be a man, don\rquote t you think?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote If I were allowed the privilege of improving myself, sir, I would choose to be a better surgeon. The practice of my craft is the prime purpose of my existence. There is no way I could be a better surgeon if I were a man, but only if I were a more advanced robot. It would please me very much indeed to be a more advanced robot.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But you would still be a robot, even so.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. Of course. To be a robot is quite acceptable to me. As I have just explained, sir, in order for one to excel at the extremely difficult and demanding practice of modern-day surgery it is necessary that one be--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote A robot, yes,\rdblquote  said Andrew, with just a note of exasperation creeping into his tone. \ldblquote But think of the subservience involved, Doctor! Consider: you\rquote re a highly skilled surgeon. You deal in the most delicate matters of life and death--you operate on some of the most important individuals in the world, and for all I know you have patients come to you from other worlds as well. And yet--and yet--a robot? You\rquote re content with that? For all your skill, you must take orders from \i anyone, \i0 any human at all: a child, a fool, a boor, a rogue. The Second Law commands it. It leaves you no choice. Right this minute I could say, \lquote Stand up, Doctor,\rquote  and you\rquote d have to stand up. \lquote Put your fingers over your face and wiggle them,\rquote  and you\rquote d wiggle. Stand on one leg, sit down on the floor, move right or left, anything I wanted to tell you, and you\rquote d obey. I could order you to disassemble yourself limb by limb, and you would. You, a great surgeon! No choice at all. A human whistles and you hop to his tune. Doesn\rquote t it offend you that I have the power to make you do whatever damned thing I please, no matter how idiotic, how trivial, how degrading?\rdblquote  \par
\tab The surgeon was unfazed. \par
\tab\ldblquote It would be my pleasure to please you, sir. With certain obvious exceptions. If your orders should happen to involve my doing any harm to you or any other human being, I would have to take the primary laws of my nature into consideration before obeying you, and in all likelihood I would \i not \i0 obey you. Naturally the First Law, which concerns my duty to human safety, would take precedence over the Second Law relating to obedience. Otherwise, obedience is my pleasure. If it would give you pleasure to require me to do certain acts that you regard as idiotic or trivial or degrading, I would perform those acts. But they would not seem idiotic or trivial or degrading to me.\rdblquote  \par
\tab There was nothing even remotely surprising to Andrew Martin in the things the robot surgeon had said. He would have found it astonishing, even revolutionary, if the robot had taken any other position. \par
\tab But even so--even so--\par
\tab The surgeon said, with not the slightest trace of impatience in his smooth bland voice, \ldblquote Now, if we may return to the subject of this extraordinary operation that you have come here to discuss, sir. I can barely comprehend the nature of what you want done. It is hard for me to visualize a situation that would require such a thing. But what I need to know, first of all, is the name of the person upon whom I am asked to perform this operation.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The name is Andrew Martin,\rdblquote  Andrew said. \ldblquote The operation is to be performed on me.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But that would be impossible, sir!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Surely you\rquote d be capable of it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Capable in a technical sense, yes. I have no serious doubt on that score, regardless of what may be asked of me, although in this case there are certain procedural issues that I would have to consider very carefully. But that is beside the point. I ask you please to bear in mind, sir, that the fundamental effect of the operation would be harmful to you.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That does not matter at all,\rdblquote  said Andrew calmly. \par
\tab\ldblquote It does to me.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Is this the robot version of the Hippocratic Oath?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Something far more stringent than that,\rdblquote  the surgeon said. \ldblquote The Hippocratic Oath is, of course, a voluntary pledge. But there is, as plainly you must be aware, something innate in my circuitry itself that controls my professional decisions. Above and beyond everything else, I must not inflict damage. I \i may \i0 not inflict damage.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote On human beings, yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Indeed. The First Law says--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t recite the First Law, Doctor. I know it at least as well as you. But the First Law simply governs the actions of robots toward human beings. I\rquote m not human, Doctor.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The surgeon reacted with a visible twitch of his shoulders and a blinking of his photoelectric eyes. It was as if what Andrew had just said had no meaning for him whatever. \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Andrew, \ldblquote I know that I seem to be quite human, and that what you\rquote re experiencing now is the robot equivalent of surprise. Nevertheless I\rquote m telling you the absolute truth. However human I may appear to you, I am simply a robot. A \i robot, \i0 Doctor. A robot is what I am, and nothing more than that. Believe me. And therefore you are free to operate on me. There is nothing in the First Law which prohibits a robot from performing actions on another robot. Even if the action that is performed should cause harm to that robot, Doctor.\rdblquote  \par
\par
