THE TIME OF YEAR arrived when Miss celebrated her birthday. Andrew had already learned that one\rquote s birthday celebration was an important event in the annual round of human life--a commemoration of the anniversary of the day that one had emerged from one\rquote s mother\rquote s womb. \par
\tab Andrew thought that it was strange that humans would choose the day of coming forth from the womb as the significant thing to commemorate. He knew something of human biology, and it seemed to him that it would be much more important to focus on the moment of the actual creation of the organism, when the sperm cell entered the ovum and the process of cell division began. Surely that was the real point of origin of any person! \par
\tab Certainly the new person was already alive--if not yet capable of independent functioning--during the nine months spent within the womb. Nor was a human being particularly capable of independent functioning immediately after leaving the womb, so the distinction between birth and pre-birth that humans insisted on drawing made very little sense to Andrew. \par
\tab He himself had been ready to perform all his programmed functions the moment the last phase of his assembly was complete and his pathways had been initialized. But a newborn child was far from able to manage on its own. Andrew could see no effective difference between a fetus that had completed its various stages of fetal development but was still inside its mother and the same fetus, a day or two later, that had emerged. One was inside and one was outside, that was all. But they were just about equally helpless. So why not celebrate the anniversary of one\rquote s moment of conception instead of the anniversary of one\rquote s release from the womb? \par
\tab The more he pondered it, though, the more he saw that there was some logic to either view. What, for example, would he select as his own birthday, assuming that robots felt any need to celebrate their birthdays? The date when the factory had begun assembling him, or the date on which his positronic brain had been installed in its case and initialization of somatic control had been keyed? Had he been \ldblquote born\rdblquote  when the first strands of his armature were being drawn together, or when the unique set of perceptions that constituted NDR-113 had gone into operation? A mere armature wasn\rquote t \i him, \i0 whatever \i he \i0 was. His positronic brain was \i him \i0 Or the combination of the positronic brain properly placed within the body that had been designed to house it. So his birthday\par
\tab Oh, it was all so confusing! And robots weren\rquote t supposed to be plagued by confusion. Their positronic minds were more complex than the simple digital \ldblquote minds\rdblquote  of non-positronic computers, which operated entirely in stark binary realms, mere patterns of on or off, yes or no, positive or negative, and that complexity could sometimes lead to moments of conflicting potential. But nevertheless robots were logical creatures who were able to find their way out of such conflicts, usually, by sorting the data in a sensible way. Why, then, was he having so much trouble comprehending this business of when one\rquote s birthday ought to be? \par
\tab Because birthdays are a purely human concept, he answered himself. They have no relevance to robots. And you are not a human being, so you do not need to worry about when your birthday ought or ought not to be celebrated. \par
\tab At any rate, it was Miss\rquote s birthday. Sir made a point of coming home early that day, even though the Regional Legislature was embroiled in some complicated debate over interplanetary free-trade zones. The whole family dressed in holiday clothes and gathered around the great slab of polished redwood that was the dining-room table and candles were lit, and Andrew served an elaborate dinner that he and Ma\rquote am had spent hours planning, and afterward Miss formally received and opened her presents. The receiving of presents--new possessions, given to you by others--was apparently a major part of the birthday-celebration ritual. \par
\tab Andrew watched, not really understanding. He knew that humans placed high importance on the owning of things, specific objects that belonged only to them, but it was very hard to comprehend what value most of those objects had for them, or why they placed such emphasis on having them. \par
\tab Little Miss, who had learned how to read only a year or two before, gave her sister a book. Not a cassette, not an infodisk, not a holocube, but an actual book, with a cover and binding and pages. Little Miss was very fond of books. So was Miss--especially books of poetry, which was a way of writing things in cryptic phrases arranged in uneven lines that Andrew found extremely mysterious. \par
\tab\ldblquote How marvelous!\rdblquote  Miss cried, when she had taken her book from its gaily covered wrapper. \ldblquote The \i Rubaiyat \i0 of Omar Khayyam! I\rquote ve always wanted it! But how did you even know there was such a thing? Who told you about it, Amanda?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I \i read \i0 about it,\rdblquote  said Little Miss, looking a trifle put out. \ldblquote You think I don\rquote t know anything at all, just because I\rquote m five years younger than you, but let me tell you, Melissa--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Girls! Girls!\rdblquote  Sir called warningly. \ldblquote Let\rquote s have no bickering at the birthday dinner!\rdblquote  \par
\tab The next present Miss opened was from her mother: a fine cashmere sweater, white and fluffy. Miss was so excited that she put it on over the sweater she was already wearing. \par
\tab And then she opened the small package that was her father\rquote s gift, and gasped; for Sir had bought her an intricate pendant of pink ivorite, carved with marvelous scrollwork so delicately worked that even Andrew\rquote s flawless vision was hard pressed to follow all its curving and interlocking patterns. Miss looked radiantly happy. She lifted it by its fine golden chain and slipped it over her head, lowering it carefully until it lay perfectly centered on the front of her new sweater. \par
\tab\ldblquote Happy birthday, Melissa,\rdblquote  Sir said. And Ma\rquote am chimed in, and Little Miss too, and they all sang the birthday song. Then Ma\rquote am called for another round of the song, and this time she gestured to Andrew, who joined in, singing along with them. \par
\tab For a moment he wondered whether he should have given Amanda some sort of present also. No, he thought, she did not seem to have expected it from him. And why should she? He wasn\rquote t a member of the family. He was an item of household machinery. The giving of birthday presents was entirely a human thing. \par
\tab It was a lovely birthday dinner. There was only one thing wrong with it, which was that Little Miss seemed bitterly envious of Miss\rquote s lovely ivorite pendant. \par
\tab She tried to hide it, of course. It was her sister\rquote s birthday dinner, after all, and she didn\rquote t want to spoil it. But all during the course of the evening Little Miss kept stealing glances at the pendant that gleamed warmly in pink and gold atop Melissa\rquote s sweater, and it took no great subtlety of perception on Andrew\rquote s part to know how unhappy she was. \par
\tab He wished there was something he could do to cheer her up. But this whole affair of birthdays, and presents, and sisters, and envy, and other such human concepts--they were really beyond his comprehension. He was a very capable robot of the kind that he was designed to be, but his designers had seen no need to give him the capacity to understand why one little girl would be upset about a beautiful object that had been given to another little girl who was her sister on the occasion of her birthday. \par
\tab A day or two later, though, Little Miss came to Andrew and said, \ldblquote Can I speak to you, Andrew?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Of course you can.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Did you like that pendant that Daddy gave Melissa?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It seemed to be very beautiful.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It \i is \i0 very beautiful. It\rquote s the most gorgeous thing I\rquote ve ever seen.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It is quite beautiful, yes,\rdblquote  Andrew said. \ldblquote  And I am sure that Sir will give you something every bit as beautiful when it is the time of your birthday.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote My birthday is three months from now,\rdblquote  Little Miss said. \par
\tab She said it as though that were an eternity away. \par
\tab Andrew waited, not quite able to determine where this conversation was heading. \par
\tab Then Little Miss went to the cabinet where she had put the piece of driftwood that she had brought from the beach the day he had gone swimming, and held it out to him. \par
\tab\ldblquote Will you make a pendant for me, Andrew? Out of this?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote A wooden pendant?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well, I don\rquote t happen to have any ivorite handy. But this is very pretty wood. You know how to carve, don\rquote t you? Or you could learn, I suppose.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m certain that my mechanical skills would be equal to the job. But I would need certain tools, and--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Here,\rdblquote  said Little Miss. \par
\tab She had taken a small knife from the kitchen. She handed it to him with an air of great gravity, as if she were giving him a whole set of sculptor\rquote s blades. \par
\tab\ldblquote This should be all you need,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote I have faith in you, Andrew.\rdblquote  \par
\tab And she took his metal hand in hers and gave it a squeeze. \par
\tab That night, in the quiet of the room where he usually stored himself when his day\rquote s chores were done, Andrew studied the piece of driftwood with great care for perhaps fifteen minutes, analyzing its grain, its density, its curvature. He gave the little knife careful scrutiny too, testing it on a piece of wood he had picked up in the garden to see how useful it would be. Then he considered Little Miss\rquote s height and what size pendant would be best suited to a girl who was still very small but was not likely to remain that way indefinitely. \par
\tab Eventually he sliced a section from the tip of the driftwood piece. The wood was very hard, but Andrew had a robot\rquote s physical strength, so the only question was whether the knife itself would withstand the demands he was placing on it. It did. \par
\tab He contemplated the section of wood that he had separated from the bigger piece. He held it, turning it, rubbing his fingers over its surface. He closed his eyes and envisioned the way it might look if he removed a bit here, a bit there--just shaved away a little over here--and also here\par
\tab Yes. \par
\tab He began to work. \par
\tab The job took him almost no time at all, once the preliminary planning had been carried out in his mind. Andrew\rquote s mechanical coordination was easily equal to such fastidious work and his eyesight was perfect and the wood seemed to yield readily enough to the things he wished to do with it. \par
\tab By the time he was finished, though, it was much too late at night to take it to Little Miss. He put it aside and gave it no further thought until morning. Just as Little Miss was about to run outside to meet the bus that took her to school each day, Andrew produced the little carving and held it out to her. She took it from him, staring in perplexity and surprise. \par
\tab\ldblquote I made it for you,\rdblquote  he said. \par
\tab\ldblquote You \i did?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i0\ldblquote From the wood you gave me last night.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, Andrew--Andrew--it\rquote s absolutely \i marvelous, \i0 Andrew! Oh, it\rquote s so fine! So beautiful! I never imagined you could make anything like it. Wait till Melissa sees it! Just wait! And I\rquote ll show it to Daddy, too--!\rdblquote  \par
\tab The horn honked outside. Little Miss tucked the carving safely in her purse and hurried out to the bus. But she turned when she was a dozen meters up the path and waved to Andrew--and blew him a kiss. \par
\tab In the evening, when Sir had come home from his stint at the Regional Capitol and Little Miss had brought forth the carving, there was a general stir over it in the household. Ma\rquote am exclaimed at great length over its loveliness and Miss was gracious enough to concede that it was nearly as attractive as the pendant she had received for her birthday. \par
\tab Sir himself was astounded. He could not believe that Andrew had carved the little trinket. \par
\tab\ldblquote Where did you get this, Mandy?\rdblquote  Mandy was what he called Little Miss, though no one else did. \par
\tab\ldblquote I told you, Daddy. Andrew made it for me. I found a piece of driftwood on the beach and he carved it out of that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote He\rquote s not supposed to be an artisan robot.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote A what?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote A woodcarver,\rdblquote  Sir said. \par
\tab\ldblquote Well, I guess that maybe he is,\rdblquote  said Little Miss. \ldblquote Maybe he\rquote s lots of things that we don\rquote t know about.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Sir looked toward Andrew. He was frowning, and he tugged thoughtfully at his mustache--Sir had a very conspicuous mustache, a great flaring woolly brush of a mustache--and he scowled the sort of scowl that Andrew, whose experience with human facial expressions was still somewhat limited, nevertheless understood to be a very serious scowl indeed. \par
\tab\ldblquote Did you actually make this thing, Andrew?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Sir.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Robots aren\rquote t capable of lying, you know.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That is not entirely correct, Sir. I could lie if I were ordered to lie, or if it were necessary for me to tell some untruth in order to keep a human being from harm, or even if my own safety were--\rdblquote  He paused. \ldblquote But I did indeed carve this for Little Miss.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And the design, too? You\rquote re responsible for that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Sir.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What did you copy it from?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Copy it, Sir?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You couldn\rquote t just have invented it out of thin air. You got it out of some book, right? Or you used a computer to plot it out for you, or else--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I assure you, Sir, I did nothing more than study the raw material for a time until I came to understand how best to carve it into some shape that would be pleasing to Little Miss. And then I carved it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Using what sort of tools, may I ask?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote A small knife from the kitchen, Sir, which Little Miss kindly provided for me.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote A knife from the kitchen,\rdblquote  Sir repeated, in an oddly flat tone. Slowly shaking his head, he hefted the carving in his hand as though he found its beauty almost incomprehensible. \ldblquote  A knife from the kitchen. She gave you a piece of driftwood and an ordinary little kitchen knife and with no other tool than that you were able to make \i this. \i0\ldblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Sir.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The next day Sir brought Andrew another piece of wood from the beach, a larger one that was bent and weathered and stained from its long immersion in the sea. He gave Andrew an electric vibro-knife, and showed him how to use it. \par
\tab He said, \ldblquote Make something out of this chunk of wood, Andrew. Anything you want to. I simply want to watch you while you\rquote re doing it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Certainly, Sir.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew pondered the driftwood for a time, and then he switched on the vibro-knife and watched the movements of its blade edge, using his very finest optical focus, until he understood what sort of results the knife would be able to produce, and then finally he began to work. Sir sat right next to him, but as Andrew set about the task of carving he became barely aware of the human being adjacent to him. He was wholly focused on his task. All that mattered to him at that moment was the piece of wood, and the vibro-knife, and the vision of the thing that he intended to bring forth from the wood. \par
\tab When he was done, he handed the carving to Sir, and went to fetch the dust-pan so that he could sweep up the shavings. Upon his return to the room he found Sir sitting motionless, staring at the carving in a kind of numb, stunned way. \par
\tab\ldblquote I asked for a household robot of the NDR series,\rdblquote  Sir said softly. \ldblquote I don\rquote t remember specifying anything about special craftsman adaptations.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Indeed, Sir. I am an NDR household robot. I have no specialized implants having to do with craft skills.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yet you made this. I saw you do it with my own eyes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That is so, Sir.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Could you make other things out of wood, do you think? Cabinets, let\rquote s say? Desks? Lamps? Large-scale sculptures?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I am unable to tell you, Sir. I have never attempted such things.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, you will now.\rdblquote  \par
\tab After that, Andrew spent very little time preparing meals and waiting at the table, or doing the other minor jobs around the house that had become part of his daily routine. He was ordered to read books on woodcarving and design, with a special emphasis on furniture-making, and one of the empty attic rooms was set aside as a workshop for him. \par
\tab Although he continued to carve small wooden trinkets for Miss and Little Miss and occasionally for Ma\rquote am as well--bracelets, earrings, necklaces, pendants--Andrew devoted much of his time, at Sir\rquote s suggestion, to such things as cabinets and desks. His designs were striking and unusual. He employed rare and exotic woods which Sir provided, and decorated them with inlays of the most intricate and ingenious patterns. \par
\tab Sir went upstairs to the workshop every day or two to inspect the latest creations. \par
\tab\ldblquote These are amazing productions, Andrew,\rdblquote  he would say again and again. \ldblquote Utterly amazing. You aren\rquote t just an artisan, do you realize that? You\rquote re a true artist. And the things you\rquote ve been turning out are works of art.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew said, \ldblquote I enjoy making them, Sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Enjoy?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Should I not be using that word?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s a little unusual to hear a robot speaking of \lquote enjoying\rquote  something, that\rquote s all. I didn\rquote t realize that robots had the capacity for feelings of that sort.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Perhaps I use the concept loosely.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Perhaps you do,\rdblquote  Sir said. \ldblquote But I\rquote m not so sure. You say that you enjoy making this furniture. What exactly do you mean by that?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote When I do the work, it makes the circuits of my brain somehow flow more easily. That seems to me to be the equivalent of the human feeling known as \lquote enjoyment.\rquote  I have heard you use the word \lquote enjoy\rquote  and I think I understand its significance. The way you use it fits the way I feel. So it seems appropriate for me to say that I enjoy making these things, Sir.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Ah. Yes.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Sir was quiet for a time. \par
\tab\ldblquote You are a very unusual robot, do you know that, Andrew?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I am entirely standard, Sir. My circuitry is modular NDR, nothing more, nothing less.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Indeed.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Does my doing this cabinetwork trouble you, Sir?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all, Andrew. Quite the contrary.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yet I sense some uneasiness in your vocal tones. There is a quality in them of--how shall I express it?--a quality of surprise? No, \lquote surprise\rquote  is inaccurate. A quality of uncertainty? Of doubt?--What I mean is that you appear to be thinking, Sir, that I am working beyond the programmed levels of my capacities.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Sir. \ldblquote That\rquote s exactly what I do think, Andrew. Well beyond your programmed levels, as a matter of fact. Not that I\rquote m troubled that you\rquote ve unexpectedly turned out to have this little streak of artistic ability in you, you understand. But I\rquote d like to know just why it\rquote s there.\rdblquote  \par
\par
