FIVE \par
\pard\b0\fs20\par
MISS HAD BEGUN to cross the threshold that truly separates girlhood from womanhood, now. She was enjoying an active social life and going off with her new friends--not all of them girls--on excursions to the mountains, to the deserts of the south, to the wilderness to the north. Her presence in the Martin house was becoming an increasingly rare event. \par
\tab So it was Little Miss--not as little as before--who filled Andrew\rquote s horizon now. She was turning into a coltish, tireless girl who loved to run great distances along the beach, with Andrew effortlessly keeping pace beside her. She went rambling in the forested areas adjacent to the house, and relied on Andrew to help her down when she had scrambled a little too far up some tree to peer into a bird\rquote s nest, or when she had trapped herself on some precarious rocky ledge that she had climbed for the sake of getting a better view of the sea. \par
\tab As ever, Andrew was vigilant and endlessly protective as Little Miss romped about. He would let her take her little tomboyish risks, yes, because they seemed to make her happy, but not without his calculating the \i real \i0 risk of anything serious happening to her, and he was always poised and ready to intervene swiftly on her behalf if that should be necessary. \par
\tab The First Law, of course, compelled Andrew to exert constant diligence to protect Little Miss from harm. But, as he sometimes told himself, he would willingly and gladly defend her against peril of any sort even if the First Law did not exist. \par
\tab That was an odd thought: that there might be no First Law. Andrew could barely conceive of that The First Law (and the Second, and the Third) were such fundamental aspects of his neural pathways that it made him dizzy to imagine himself without them. And yet he \i had \i0 imagined it. Andrew was puzzled by that: how strange, having a capacity to imagine the unimaginable! It made him feel almost human, when paradoxical concepts like that went through his mind. \par
\tab But what did \i almost \i0 human mean? That was another paradox, and an even more dizzying one. Either you were human or you were not How could there be any sort of intermediate state? \par
\tab You are a robot, Andrew reminded himself sternly. \par
\tab You are a product of the United States Robots and Mechanical Men Corporation. \par
\tab And then Andrew would look at Little Miss and a sensation of great joy and warmth would spread through his positronic brain--a sensation that he had come to identify as \ldblquote love\rdblquote --and he would have to remind himself, allover again, that he was nothing more than a cleverly designed structure of metal and plastic with an artificial platinum-iridium brain inside his chrome-steel skull, and he had no right to feel emotions, or to think paradoxical thoughts, or to do any other such complex and mysterious human thing. Even his woodworking art--and he did allow himself to think of it as \ldblquote art\rdblquote --was simply a function of the skills with which he had been programmed by his designers. \par
\tab Little Miss never allowed herself to forget that the very first piece of woodcarving Andrew had done had been for her. She was rarely without the little pendant that he had made for her out of that piece of driftwood, wearing it on a silver chain about her neck and reaching up to finger it fondly again and again. \par
\tab It was she who first objected to Sir\rquote s casual habit of giving away Andrew\rquote s productions to anyone who visited the house. He would proudly show his guests Andrew\rquote s latest work, and then, when the predictable expressions of admiration and even envy were uttered, would grandly exclaim, \ldblquote Do you really like it that much? Then take it with you! By all means, take it! My pleasure! There are plenty more where that one came from!\rdblquote  \par
\tab One day Sir bestowed a particularly intricate abstract carving--a shining spheroid made of slender interwoven strips of redwood with inlays of manzanita and madrone wood--on the Speaker of the Legislature. The Speaker was a loud-voiced red-faced man who had always seemed particularly dull-witted and vulgar to Little Miss, and she very much doubted that he had any ability to see the beauty in Andrew\rquote s work. No doubt he was simply being diplomatic when he had praised the carving, and he would simply toss it thoughtlessly into some closet when he got it home. \par
\tab Little Miss said, after the Speaker had left, \ldblquote Come on, Dad. You shouldn\rquote t have given that to him and you know it!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But he liked it, Mandy. He said he thought it was extremely beautiful.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It \i is \i0 extremely beautiful. So is the beach in front of our house. If he said the beach was extremely beautiful, would you have deeded it over to him?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Mandy, Mandy--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well? Would you?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s a false parallel,\rdblquote  Sir said. \ldblquote Obviously you don\rquote t go handing away chunks of your real estate to people on a whim. But a small carving--given as a modest expression of affection to a friend of many years\rquote  standing who also happens to be a highly influential political leader--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Are you saying it was a \i bribe?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i0 For an instant real anger flashed in Sir\rquote s eyes. But it died away almost as fast as it had come and the usual twinkle with which he regarded his youngest daughter returned. \par
\tab\ldblquote You don\rquote t really mean that, do you, Mandy? You understand that my gift to the Speaker was merely an act of hospitality, right?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well--yes. Yes. I\rquote m sorry, Dad. What I said was uncalled-for and mean.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Sir smiled. \ldblquote It was, yes. --Is it that you wanted that carving for yourself? Your room is already filled with things that Andrew has made, you know. The whole house is. We can\rquote t give them away as fast as he makes them.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s the whole point I was trying to make. That you \i give \i0 them away.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Sir\rquote s smile grew broader. \ldblquote Well, what would you prefer that I do? Sell them to people?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote As a matter of fact, yes. That\rquote s exactly what I would prefer.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Sir said, looking astonished, \ldblquote It isn\rquote t like you to be greedy, Mandy.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What does greed have to do with this?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Surely you must understand that we already have more than enough money. Quite apart from the complete impropriety of my putting a price tag on some object that a guest in my house might happen to admire, it would be absurd for me to go in for trivial profiteering of any such kind.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m not saying that \i we \i0 should try to make money on the things Andrew carves. But what about Andrew?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What about him?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote He does the work. He should have the money.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Sir blinked. \ldblquote Andrew\rquote s a robot, Mandy.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, I know that, Dad\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Robots aren\rquote t people, sweet. They\rquote re machines, remember? Like telephones, like computers. What imaginable use would a machine have for money? Robots don\rquote t go shopping. Robots don\rquote t take holidays in Hawaii. Robots don\rquote t--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m serious, Dad. This is an important issue. Andrew spent hours making that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote So?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Robot or not, he\rquote s got the right to benefit from the results of his labor. When you coolly hand out the things he makes as gifts to your friends or political associates, the way you do, you\rquote re exploiting him, did you ever stop to think of that, Dad? He may be a machine but he\rquote s not a slave. And also he\rquote s an \i artist. \i0 He\rquote s entitled to be compensated for making those things. Maybe not when he makes them for us, but when you give them away like that to other people--\rdblquote  Little Miss paused. \ldblquote Do you remember the French Revolution, Dad? --No, I don\rquote t mean do you remember it literally. But its basic issue was the exploiting of the working classes by the aristocracy. Robots are our new working classes. And if we go on treating our robots the way the dukes and duchesses treated their peasants--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Sir smiled gently. \par
\tab\ldblquote The last thing we need to worry about, Mandy, is an uprising by our robots. The Three Laws\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The Three Laws, the Three Laws, the Three Laws! I \i hate \i0 the Three Laws! You can\rquote t deprive Andrew of the benefit of the work he does. You can\rquote t! It isn\rquote t \i fait; \i0 Dad!\rdblquote  \par
\tab The fury in Little Miss\rquote s voice cut off the rest of Sir\rquote s disquisition on the Laws of Robotics before he had barely managed to frame his words. \par
\tab He said instead, after a moment, \ldblquote You really feel strongly about this, don\rquote t you, Mandy?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. Yes, I do.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote All right. Let me think about it. And perhaps we can actually work something out for Andrew along the lines that you\rquote re suggesting.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You promise?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I promise,\rdblquote  said Sir, and Little Miss knew that everything was going to be all right, for her father\rquote s promises to her were inviolable contracts --always had been, always would be. \par
\tab Some time went by, and other visitors came to the house, and everyone who saw Andrew\rquote s work responded with the usual praise. But Little Miss, who was watching closely, observed with pleasure that her father had stopped giving Andrew\rquote s things away, no matter how effusive the praise might be. \par
\tab On the other hand, it happened on several occasions that some guest would say, \ldblquote You don\rquote t think I could buy that from you, do you, Gerald?\rdblquote  And Sir, looking uncomfortable, would simply shrug and reply that he wasn\rquote t quite sure whether he wanted to get into the business of selling such things. \par
\tab Little Miss wondered why her father was sidestepping the issue like that. Sidestepping things wasn\rquote t normally part of his nature. And it wasn\rquote t as though anyone was likely to accuse him of deliberately setting out to earn money by peddling Andrew\rquote s work to his house guests. Obviously Gerald Martin was in no need of picking up a bit of extra money on the side that way. But if the offers were made in good faith, though, why not accept them? \par
\tab She let the issue rest, nevertheless. She knew her father well enough to understand that the matter was still open, and would be attended to in due course. \par
\tab Then another visitor came: John Feingold, Sir\rquote s lawyer. The offices of Feingold\rquote s law firm were in the San Francisco area, where despite the general decentralization of city life that had been going on all during the current century a good many people still preferred to live. But though San Francisco was only a short journey south of the wild strip of coast where the Martins lived, a visit from John Feingold to the Martin house was a relatively unusual thing. Usually Sir went down to San Francisco whenever he had business to discuss with Feingold. So Little Miss knew that something special must be up. \par
\tab Feingold was an easy-going white-haired man with florid pink skin, a pudgy belly, and a warm, amiable smile. He preferred to dress in older styles of clothing and the rims of his contact lenses were tinted a bright green, a fashion so rare nowadays that it was all that Little Miss could do to keep from giggling whenever she saw the lawyer. Sir had to shoot her a stern glance now and then when he detected a fit of laughter coming over her in Feingold\rquote s presence. \par
\tab Feingold and Sir settled down before the fireplace in the great central room of the house and Sir handed him a small inlaid plaque that Andrew had produced a few days before. \par
\tab The lawyer nodded. He turned it over and over in his hand, rubbed its polished surface appreciatively, held it up to the light at various angles. \par
\tab\ldblquote Beautiful,\rdblquote  he said, finally. \ldblquote Extraordinarily fine work, all right. Your robot did it?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. How did you know that?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve heard some talk. It\rquote s no secret, Gerald, that you\rquote ve got a robot here who\rquote s a master craftsman in wood.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Sir glanced up at Andrew, who was standing quietly in the shadows to one side. \ldblquote Do you hear that, Andrew? You\rquote re famous all up and down California. --But you\rquote re wrong about one thing, John. Andrew isn\rquote t simply a master craftsman. He\rquote s an out-and-out \i artist, \i0 nothing less.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Indeed he is,\rdblquote  Feingold said. \ldblquote That\rquote s the only word for him. This is a wonderful piece.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Would you like to own it?\rdblquote  Sir asked. \par
\tab Feingold\rquote s eyes widened in surprise. \ldblquote  Are you offering it to me, Gerald?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I might be. It all depends on how much you\rquote d be willing to pay for it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Feingold grunted as though Sir had poked him in the ribs with a rigid finger. He sat back sharply, rearranging himself with some care, and for a moment he did not reply. \par
\tab Then he said, in an entirely different voice, \ldblquote I hadn\rquote t been aware that you\rquote ve been undergoing financial reverses lately, Gerald.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I haven\rquote t.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then--pardon me if I sound a little confused--why on Earth would you want to--\rdblquote  \par
\tab His voice trailed off. \par
\tab\ldblquote Sell you that little carving?\rdblquote  Sir finished for him. \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. Sell it. I know you\rquote ve been giving away a great many of the things that Andrew has made. People have told me that it\rquote s practically impossible to come here without being offered something. I\rquote ve seen a few of the things that they\rquote ve been given. There\rquote s never been a question of money changing hands, am I right? And now--completely leaving out of the discussion the fact that I\rquote m not a collector of little wooden carvings, no matter how lovely they might be--you baffle me by asking me if I want to purchase one! Why? I doubt very much that you have any special reason for wanting me to pay for what everybody else gets free. And you can\rquote t possibly need the money. You\rquote ve just told me that yourself. In any event how much would you be able to get for an object like this? Five hundred dollars? A thousand? If you\rquote re still as wealthy as I know you to be, Gerald, what difference could the odd five hundred or thousand make to you?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not to me. To Andrew.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Your estimate happens to be right on the mark, John. I think I could get a thousand for this little thing. And I\rquote ve been offered rather more than that for chairs and desks that Andrew has made. Not just one-shot purchases but entire distribution deals for large-scale production. If I had accepted any of the offers, there\rquote d be a fine fat bank account built up by now, entirely on the proceeds of Andrew\rquote s woodworking--something up in the hundreds of thousands already, I suspect.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Feingold fussed with his epaulets and collar-studs. \ldblquote Good heavens, Gerald, I can\rquote t make any sense out of any of this. A rich man making himself richer by putting his robot to work in some sort of cottage industry--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve already told you, John, that the money wouldn\rquote t be for me. This is all for Andrew\rquote s sake. I want to start selling his products and I want the money to be banked under the name of Andrew Martin.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote A bank account in the name of a robot?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Exactly. And that\rquote s why I\rquote ve asked you to come up here today. I want to know whether it would be legal to establish an account in Andrew\rquote s name--an account that Andrew himself would control, you understand, entirely his own money, which he would be able to use absolutely as he pleases--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Feingold said, sounding mystified, \ldblquote Legal? For a robot to earn and save money? I just couldn\rquote t say. There are no precedents, so far as I\rquote ve ever heard. I doubt that there\rquote s any law against it, but even so--robots aren\rquote t people. How can they have bank accounts, then?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Corporations aren\rquote t people either, except in the most abstract sense: a legal fiction, as you would term it. Yet corporations have bank accounts.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well, I grant you that. But corporations have been recognized in the eyes of the law for centuries as entities qualified to own property of all sorts. Robots, Gerald, have no legal rights at all, as surely you must be aware. And simply as a procedural matter, let me remind you that corporations also have corporate officers, and they sign the papers that establish the bank accounts. Who would open Andrew\rquote s account? You? And would it be Andrew\rquote s account, if you opened it?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve opened bank accounts in the names of my children,\rdblquote  Sir replied. \ldblquote Nevertheless the accounts are theirs. Besides, Andrew can sign his name as well as you or I.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. Yes, of course, I suppose he can.\rdblquote  Feingold leaned back until his chair creaked. \ldblquote Let me think, Gerald. This is all so unusual. Is there really any legislation specifically forbidding robots to own property, or is it simply \i assumed \i0 that they can\rquote t, because the idea is so far from the main stream that nobody\rquote s ever given a thought to it? I\rquote d have to research it before I could give you an opinion. Quite possibly there are no such laws, precisely because a robot having assets is such a peculiar notion that it hasn\rquote t been deemed necessary to give it any consideration. Nobody has bothered to pass laws forbidding trees to have bank accounts, after all, or lawnmowers--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Cats and dogs have had bank accounts. Trust funds for their upkeep, left to them by their loving owners,\rdblquote  Sir said. \ldblquote The courts have no objection to that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Another good point, yes. Although cats and dogs are living creatures, at least. Robots are inanimate.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t see what difference that makes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You ought to bear in mind, Gerald, that there\rquote s a certain prejudice against robots in our society, a certain fear, I might almost say, that doesn\rquote t extend to cats and dogs. It might well be that someone \i has \i0 put laws on the books restricting the rights of robots to hold property. But that\rquote s easily enough checked. --Let\rquote s assume that it is legal. How would you go about it? Take Andrew down to the bank and let him speak to the manager?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote d simply have the forms sent here for Andrew\rquote s signature. There shouldn\rquote t be any need for a personal appearance on his part. But what I need to find out from you, John, is what I can do to protect Andrew--and myself, I suppose--against negative public reaction. Even though it may well be legal for him to have a bank account, there probably will be people who aren\rquote t going to like the idea.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote How will they find out?\rdblquote  Feingold asked. \par
\tab\ldblquote How will we keep them from finding out?\rdblquote  said Sir. \ldblquote If someone buys an item from him and makes a check payable to Andrew Martin, say--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Um. Yes.\rdblquote  Feingold\rquote s gaze seemed to turn inward for a moment. Then he said, \ldblquote Well, one thing we could do is to set up a corporation to handle all finances in his name--a corporation with a nice impersonal name, something like West Coast Wood Artistry, Ltd.--and Andrew can be the president and sole stockholder, though we could make ourselves members of the board of directors. That will place a layer of legalistic insulation between him and the hostile world. It ought to be enough, Gerald. Whenever Andrew wants to purchase something, he can simply draw a salary from the corporation treasury. Or declare a dividend for himself. The fact that he\rquote s a robot won\rquote t have to be a matter of public record. The incorporation forms will only need the names of the stockholders--not their birth certificates. Of course, he\rquote ll have to begin filing income tax returns. But the revenue people aren\rquote t going to come around to find out whether Taxpayer Andrew Martin is a human being or not. All they\rquote ll care about is whether Taxpayer Martin pays his taxes on time.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Good. Good. Anything else?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not that I can think of offhand. If I come up with anything else once I\rquote ve run a search for precedents, I\rquote ll let you know. But I suspect it\rquote s going to work. Nobody\rquote s likely to stop you so long as you go about things quietly and obey the absolute letter of the corporation law. And if anyone does find out what\rquote s going on and doesn\rquote t like it, well, it\rquote ll be up to them to take action against you to stop it--provided they can show that they\rquote ve got legal standing to intervene.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And if someone does, John? Will you take the case if a suit is brought against us?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Certainly. For an appropriate retainer.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What would be appropriate, do you think?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Feingold smiled. \ldblquote Something along the lines of that,\rdblquote  he said, and pointed to the wooden plaque. \par
\tab\ldblquote Fair enough,\rdblquote  said Sir. \par
\tab\ldblquote Not that I\rquote m a collector, you understand. But it does have a certain artistic appeal.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Indeed it does,\rdblquote  said Sir. \par
\tab Feingold chuckled and turned to the robot. \ldblquote  Andrew, you\rquote re going to be--well, not a rich man, but a rich robot. Does that please you?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, sir.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And what do you plan to do with all the money you\rquote re going to make?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Pay for things, sir, which otherwise Sir would have had to pay for. It would save him expense, sir.\rdblquote  \par
