\pard\b0\f2\fs20\par
\f0 ANDREW SUMMONED LITTLE MISS. Not so much for his own sake, but because Sir\rquote s anger had been so intense that Andrew feared for the old man\rquote s health, and Little Miss was the only person in the world who could soothe him out of such an irascible mood. \par
\tab Sir was in his upstairs bedroom when she arrived. He had been there for two hours. Andrew showed Little Miss up the stairs and halted, hesitating, outside the room as she began to enter it. Sir could be seen pacing back and forth, moving with such determination and ferocity that he seemed to be wearing a track in the antique oriental carpet. He paid no attention to the two figures in the hallway. \par
\tab Little Miss glanced back at Andrew. \par
\tab\ldblquote Why are you waiting out there?\rdblquote  she asked. \par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t think it would be useful for me to venture near Sir just now, Little Miss.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t be foolish.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I am the one who upset him so.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, I realize that. But he\rquote s surely over it by now. Come on in with me, and between us we\rquote ll get this thing cleared up in no time.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew could hear the rhythmic angry sound of Sir\rquote s steady pacing. \ldblquote With all respect, Little Miss, it does not seem to me that he is over it in the least. I believe he is still quite troubled. And if I irritate him further --No, Little Miss. I am unable to enter his room. Not until you assure me that he is calm enough so that I can safely be seen by him.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Little Miss stared at Andrew a moment. Then she nodded and said, \ldblquote All right, Andrew. I understand.\rdblquote  \par
\tab She went inside. Andrew heard the rhythm of Sir\rquote s anguished pacing begin to slow a bit. He heard voices: first that of Little Miss, speaking gently and calmly, and then that of Sir, erupting in torrents of volcanic wrath, and then Little Miss again, as quietly as before, and then Sir, not quite as frenziedly. And then Little Miss, still calmly but this time not gently: speaking quite firmly, in fact. \par
\tab The whole while, Andrew had no idea what was being said. It would not have been difficult for him to adjust his audio receptors to pick up the conversation clearly. But that seemed inappropriate to him; and so the only adjustment he had made was in the opposite direction, allowing him to monitor the conversation sufficiently to know whether his help might be needed, but not so that he could understand the individual words. \par
\tab After a time Little Miss appeared at the doorway and said, \ldblquote Andrew, would you step in here now?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote As I said before, I am extremely concerned about the state of Sir\rquote s emotional level, Little Miss. If I were to enter, and provoke him all over again--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote His emotional level is fine, Andrew. Blowing off a little steam isn\rquote t going to kill him. It\rquote s good for him, as a matter of fact. Now come on in here. Come in.\rdblquote  \par
\tab It was a direct order--coupled with a lessening of First Law potentials. Andrew had no choice but to obey. \par
\tab He found Sir sitting in his enormous winged armchair by the window--the mahogany-and-leather armchair that Andrew had made for him fifteen years before--with a lap-robe wrapped about him. He was indeed calm again, but there was a steely glint in his eye, and--sitting enthroned the way he was--he had the look about him of an angry old emperor plagued by unruly subordinates. He ignored Andrew\rquote s presence completely. \par
\tab Little Miss said, \ldblquote All right, Father. We can discuss this quietly and rationally, can\rquote t we?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Sir shrugged. \ldblquote I try to discuss everything quietly and rationally. I always have.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, you have, Father.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But this, Mandy--this total absurdity--this monstrous nonsense that Andrew has thrown at me--!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Father!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry. I can\rquote t stay calm when I\rquote m confronted with absolute craziness.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You know that Andrew is inherently incapable of craziness. Craziness just isn\rquote t included in his specifications.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote When he talks about getting his freedom--his \i freedom, \i0 by God!--what else can it be but craziness?\rdblquote  And Sir began to sputter and turn red again. \par
\tab Andrew had never seen Sir in such a state--never. Once more he began to feel uneasy about being present in the room, and thus setting up such a threat to the old man\rquote s constitution. Sir seemed almost on the verge of an apoplectic fit. And if something should happen to him--something that would be a direct result of Andrew\rquote s having begun all this--\par
\tab Little Miss said, \ldblquote Stop it, Father! Just stop it! You have no right to throw a tantrum over this!\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew was astonished to hear Little Miss speaking to her father so harshly, so defiantly. She sounded like a mother scolding a cranky child. Suddenly it struck him that among human beings time must eventually reverse all the normal generational roles: that Sir, once so dynamic and autocratic and all-knowing, was now as weak and vulnerable as a child, and it was Little Miss\rquote s responsibility to guide and direct him as he struggled to understand the bewildering nature of the world. \par
\tab It seemed a little strange to Andrew, too, that they would be enacting this highly charged scene in front of him. But of course no one in the Martin family had hesitated to talk in front of Andrew for thirty years--not even about the most intimate matters. Why should they feel any inhibitions in his presence? He was only a robot. \par
\tab\ldblquote Freedom--\rdblquote  Sir said. His voice was thick in his throat. \ldblquote For a \i robot!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote\i0 It\rquote s an unusual concept, yes. I admit that, Father. But why are you taking it as such a personal affront?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Am I? I\rquote m taking it as an affront against logic! An affront against common sense! Look, Mandy, what would you say if your front porch came to you and said, \lquote I want my freedom. I want to move to Chicago and be a front porch there. I think being a front porch in Chicago would be personally more fulfilling than remaining in this place.\rquote  \ldblquote  \par
\tab Andrew saw a muscle flicker in Little Miss\rquote s cheek. He understood abruptly that Sir\rquote s vehement reaction to his request must have some connection with Ma\rquote am\rquote s decision, years ago, to end her marriage to Sir and leave, to seek her freedom as a single woman far away. \par
\tab Human beings were so complicated! \par
\tab Little Miss said, \ldblquote  A front porch can\rquote t say anything. Or decide to move itself anywhere else. Front porches aren\rquote t intelligent. Andrew is.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Artificial intelligence.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Father, you sound like the worst sort of Society-for-Humanity Fundamentalist bigot! Andrew has lived with you for decades. You know him as well as you know any member of your own family. --What am I saying? He \i is \i0 a member of your own family. Now, suddenly, you begin talking about him as though he\rquote s nothing but some ingenious kind of carpet sweeper! Andrew is a \i person \i0 and you know that very well.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote An artificial person,\rdblquote  Sir said. But some of the conviction and force had left his tone. \par
\tab\ldblquote Artificial, yes. That\rquote s beside the point. This is the Twenty-Second Century, Father--and pretty far along in the Twenty-Second Century at that. Surely we\rquote re capable by now of recognizing that robots are intricate and sensitive organisms that have distinctive personalities, that have feelings, that have--well, that have \i souls. \i0\ldblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote d hate to have to defend that point in court,\rdblquote  Sir said. He said it quietly, with a touch of amusement in his voice where the rancor had been just a few moments before. So he was regaining some control over himself, apparently. Andrew felt a sensation of relief. \par
\tab\ldblquote Nobody\rquote s asking you to defend it in court,\rdblquote  said Little Miss. \ldblquote Only to accept it within your own heart. Andrew wants you to give him a document saying that he\rquote s a free individual. He\rquote s willing to pay you generously for that document, unnecessary though any payment should be. It would be a simple statement of his autonomy. What\rquote s so terrible about that, may I ask?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t want Andrew to leave me,\rdblquote  said Sir sullenly. \par
\tab\ldblquote Ah! That\rquote s it! That\rquote s the crux, isn\rquote t it, Father?\rdblquote  \par
\tab There was no fire in Sir\rquote s eyes now. He seemed lost in self-pity. \ldblquote I\rquote m an old man. My wife is long gone, my older daughter is a stranger to me, my younger daughter has moved out and is on her own in the world. I\rquote m all alone in this house--except for Andrew. And now he wants to move out too. Well, he can\rquote t. Andrew is \i mine. \i0 He belongs to me and I have the right to tell him to stay here, whether he likes it or not. He\rquote s had a damned easy time of it all these years, and if he thinks he can simply abandon me now that I\rquote m getting old and sickly, he can--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Father--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote He can just forget about it!\rdblquote  Sir cried. \ldblquote Forget it! Forget it! Forget it!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re getting yourself worked up again, Father.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What if I am?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Slow down, ease back. When did Andrew say anything about leaving you?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Sir looked confused. \ldblquote Why, what else could he have meant by wanting his freedom?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote A piece of paper is all he wants. A legal document. A bunch of words. He doesn\rquote t intend to go anywhere. What are you imagining, that he\rquote ll run off to Europe and set up a carpentry workshop there? No. No. He\rquote ll stay right here. He\rquote ll still be as loyal as ever. If you give him an order, he\rquote ll obey it without question, as he always has. Whatever you say. That won\rquote t change. Nothing will, really. Andrew wouldn\rquote t so much as be able to step outside the house if you told him not to. He can\rquote t help that. It\rquote s built in. All he wants is a form of words, Father. He wants to be called free. Is that so horrible? Is it so threatening to your Hasn\rquote t he earned it, Father?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote So this is what you believe, is it? Some new nonsense that you\rquote ve gotten into your head?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not nonsense, Father. And not new, either. Heavens, Andrew and I have been talking about this for years!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Talking about it for years, have you? Years?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote For years, yes, discussing it over and over again. It was my idea in the first place, as a matter of fact. I told him it was ridiculous for him to have to think of himself as some sort of walking gadget, when in fact he\rquote s so very much more than that. He didn\rquote t react at all well when I first proposed it to him. But then we went on talking, and after a time I saw that he was beginning to come around, and then he told me very straightforwardly that he did very much want to be free. \lquote Good,\rquote  I said. \lquote Tell my father and it\rquote ll all be arranged.\rquote  But he was afraid to. He kept on postponing it, because he was afraid you would be hurt. Finally I \i made \i0 him put it up to you.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Sir shrugged. \ldblquote It was a foolish thing to do. He doesn\rquote t know what freedom is. How can he? He\rquote s a robot.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You keep underestimating him, Father. He\rquote s a very special robot. He reads. He thinks about what he\rquote s read. He learns and grows from year to year. Maybe when he came here he was just a simple mechanical man like all the rest of them, but the capacity for growth was there in his pathways, whether his makers knew it or not, and he\rquote s made good use of that capacity. Father, I know Andrew and I tell you that he\rquote s every bit as complex a creature as--as--you and me.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Nonsense, girl.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How can you say that? He feels things inside. You must be aware of that. I\rquote m not sure \i what \i0 he feels, most of the time, but I don\rquote t know what \i you \i0 feel inside a lot of the time either, and you\rquote ve got the capacity for facial expression and all kinds of other body language that he doesn\rquote t. When you talk to him you see right away that he reacts to all kinds of abstract concepts--love, fear, beauty, loyalty, a hundred others--just as you and I do. What else counts but that? If someone else\rquote s reactions are very much like your own, how can you help but think that that someone else must be very much like yourself?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote He isn\rquote t like us,\rdblquote  Sir said. \ldblquote He\rquote s something entirely different.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote He\rquote s \i someone \i0 entirely different,\rdblquote  Little Miss said. \ldblquote  And not as different as you want to have me believe.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Sir shrugged. His face had turned gray now where it had been mottled with angry red blotches before, and he looked very, very old and weary. \par
\tab He was silent for a long while, staring at his feet, pulling his lap-robe tighter around him. He still looked like an old emperor sitting sternly upright on his throne, but now he was more like an emperor who was seriously considering the possibility of abdicating. \par
\tab\ldblquote All right,\rdblquote  he said finally. There was a note of bitterness in his tone. \ldblquote You win, Mandy. If you want me to agree with you that Andrew is a person instead of a machine, I agree. Andrew is a person. There. Are you happy now?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I never said he was a person, Father.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote As a matter of fact, you did. That was precisely the word you used.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote You corrected me. You said he was an \i artificial \i0 person, and I accepted the correction.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well, then. So be it. We agree that Andrew is an artificial person. What of it? How does calling him an artificial person instead of a robot change anything? We\rquote re just playing games with words. A counterfeit banknote may be regarded as a banknote, but it\rquote s still counterfeit. And you can call a robot an artificial person, but he\rquote ll still be--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Father, what he wants is for you to grant him his freedom. He will continue to live here and do everything in his power to make your life pleasant and comfortable, as he has since the day he came here. But he wants you to tell him that he\rquote s free.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s a meaningless statement, Mandy.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote To you, maybe. Not to him.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No. I\rquote m old, yes, but I\rquote m not quite senile, not yet, at least. What we\rquote re talking about here is establishing a gigantic legal precedent. Giving robots their freedom isn\rquote t going to abolish the Three Laws, but it sure as anything is going to open up a vast realm of legal wrangling about robot rights, robot grievances, robot this and that. Robots will be running into the courts and suing people for making them do unpleasant work, or failing to let them have vacations, or simply being unkind to them. Robots will start suing U. S. Robots and Mechanical Men for building the Three Laws into their brains, because some shyster will claim it\rquote s an infringement of their constitutional rights to life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness. Robots will want to vote. Oh, don\rquote t you see, Mandy? It\rquote ll be an immense headache for everybody.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It doesn\rquote t have to be,\rdblquote  Little Miss replied. \ldblquote This doesn\rquote t have to be a worldwide cause c\'e9l\'e8bre. It\rquote s simply an understanding between Andrew and us. All that we actually want is a privately executed legal document, Father, drawn up by John Feingold, signed by you, witnessed by me, given to Andrew, which will stipulate that he--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No. That would be utterly worthless. Look, Mandy, I sign the paper and then I die, and Andrew stands up on his hind legs and says, \lquote So long, everybody, I\rquote m a free robot and I\rquote m heading out now to seek fame and fortune, and here\rquote s the paper that proves it,\rquote  and the first time he opens his mouth and says that to someone they\rquote ll laugh in his face and tear up his little piece of meaningless paper for him and ship him back to the factory to be dismantled. Because the piece of paper won\rquote t have given him any kind of protection that has the slightest validity in our society. No. No. If you insist on my doing this nonsensical thing, I have to do it the right way or else I won\rquote t bother at all. We can\rquote t simply give Andrew his freedom just by drawing up a little paper involving just us. This is a matter for the courts.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Very well. Then we do it through the courts.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But don\rquote t you realize what that would mean?\rdblquote  Sir demanded. He was angry again. \ldblquote All the issues that I just raised will be certain to come out. There\rquote ll be tremendous controversy. And then the filing of briefs--the appeals--the public outcry--and ultimately the verdict. Which will be against us, without any question.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He glared at Andrew. \ldblquote See here, you!\rdblquote  There was a harsh grating quality in Sir\rquote s voice that Andrew had never heard before. \ldblquote Do you comprehend what we\rquote ve been saying here? The only way I can free you, if it\rquote s going to have the slightest meaning, is to do it by recognized legal means. But there \i are \i0 no recognized legal means for freeing robots. Once this thing gets into the courts, not only are you going to fail to achieve your goal, but the court will take official cognizance of an the money that you\rquote ve been amassing, and you\rquote re going to lose that too. They\rquote ll tell you that a robot has no legal right to earn money or establish bank accounts to keep it in, and either they\rquote ll confiscate it outright or they\rquote ll force me to take it away from you myself, though I don\rquote t have any need for it whatever or any desire to have it. That\rquote ll be an embarrassment to me and a dead loss to you. You still won\rquote t be free, whatever that may mean to you, and you won\rquote t have your precious bank account either. Well, Andrew? Is all this rigmarole worth the chance of losing your money?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Freedom is a priceless thing, Sir,\rdblquote  Andrew said. \ldblquote And the chance of gaining my freedom is worth any amount of money that I may possess.\rdblquote  \par
\par
\par
\pard\keepn\s1\b\fs28 EIGHT \par
\pard\b0\fs20\par
IT TROUBLED ANDREW greatly that the process of seeking his freedom might cause further distress for Sir. Sir was very fragile now--there was no disguising that, no avoiding the reality of it--and anything that might be a drain on his flagging energies, anything that might upset or disturb or in any way trouble him, might all too readily endanger his life. \par
\tab And yet Andrew felt it essential that he press onward with his legal action, now that he had brought the matter up. To turn away from it at this point would be a betrayal of his own integrity. It would mean a repudiation of the independent and self-actuated persona that he had felt burgeoning within his positronic brain for year after year. \par
\tab At first the promptings of that persona had bewildered and even alarmed him. It seemed wrong to him, a flaw in his design, that it should be there at all. But over the course of time he had come to accept its existence as a real thing. Freedom--the state of not being a slave, the state of not being a \i thing--\i0 was\i  \i0 what that persona demanded now. And had to have. \par
\tab He knew there were risks. The court might share his attitude that freedom was a thing without price--but could easily rule that there was no price, however great, for which a robot might be able to buy his freedom. \par
\tab Andrew was willing to take his chances on that. But the other risk, the risk to Sir\rquote s well-being, troubled him deeply. \par
\tab\ldblquote I fear for Sir,\rdblquote  he told Little Miss. \ldblquote The publicity--the controversy--the uproar--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Don\rquote t worry, Andrew. He\rquote ll be shielded from everything, I promise you. John Feingold\rquote s lawyers will see to that This is entirely a procedural matter. It isn\rquote t going to involve my father personally at all.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And if he is called into court?\rdblquote  Andrew asked. \par
\tab\ldblquote He won\rquote t be.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote If he is, though,\rdblquote  Andrew persisted. \ldblquote He is my owner, after all. And a famous former member of the Legislature besides. What if there is a subpoena? He\rquote ll have to appear. He will be asked why he thinks I should have my freedom. He doesn\rquote t even really believe that I should--he\rquote s going along with this entirely for your sake, Little Miss, I have no doubt about that--and he will have to come into court, sick and old as he is, to testify in favor of something about which he has deep reservations. It will kill him, Little Miss.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote He won\rquote t be called into court. \ldblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote How can you assure me of that? I have no right to allow him to come to harm. I have no \i ability \i0 to allow him to come to harm. --I think I have to withdraw my petition.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You can\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Little Miss. \par
\tab\ldblquote But if my going to court should be the direct cause of your father\rquote s death--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You\rquote re getting overwrought, Andrew. And putting interpretations on the First Law that are completely unwarranted. My father isn\rquote t a defendant in this case, and he\rquote s not the plaintiff either, and he\rquote s not even going to be a witness. Don\rquote t you think John Feingold is capable of protecting someone who was as well known and important in this Region as my father from the nuisance of being called into court? I tell you, Andrew, he will be shielded. Some of the most powerful people in this Region will see to that, if it becomes necessary. But it won\rquote t become necessary.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I wish I could be as sure of that as you are.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I wish you could too. Trust me, Andrew. He\rquote s my father, let me remind you. I love hint more than anything in the--well, I love him very deeply. I wouldn\rquote t dream of letting you go ahead with this case if I saw any danger to him in it You\rquote ve got to believe that, Andrew.\rdblquote  \par
\tab And in the end he did. He still was uneasy about the possibility of Sir\rquote s becoming involved. But Little Miss had given him enough assurance to proceed. \par
\tab A man from the Feingold office came to the house with papers for him to sign, and Andrew signed them--proudly, with a flourish, the bold \i Andrew Martin \i0 signature in firm up-and-down strokes that he had been using on his checks ever since the founding of his corporation so many years before. \par
\tab The petition was filed with the Regional Court. Months went by, and nothing in particular happened. Occasionally some dreary legal document would arrive, elaborately bound in the traditional stiff covers, and Andrew would scan it quickly and sign it and return it, and then nothing more would be heard for another few months. \par
\tab Sir was very frail now. Andrew found himself thinking, sometimes, that it might be for the best if Sir died peacefully before the case ever came to court, so that he would be spared the possibility of any kind of emotional turmoil. \par
\tab The thought was horrifying to him. Andrew banished it from his mind. \par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote re on the docket,\rdblquote  Little Miss told him finally. \ldblquote It won\rquote t be long now.\rdblquote  \par
\tab And, exactly as Sir had predicted, the proceedings were far from simple. \par
\tab Little Miss had assured him that it would merely be a matter of appearing before a judge, presenting a petition for a declaration of his status as a free robot, and sitting back to wait out the time it took for the judge to do some research, study the legal precedents, and issue his ruling. The California district of the Regional Court was notoriously farseeing in its interpretation of legal matters and there was every reason, so Little Miss asserted, to believe that the judge would, in the course of time, rule in Andrew\rquote s favor and issue some sort of certificate that gave him the free status he sought. \par
\tab The first indication that things were going to be more complicated than that came when the offices of Feingold and Feingold received notice from the Regional Court--Judge Harold Kramer, presiding over the Fourth Circuit--that counter-petitions had been filed in the matter of Martin vs. Martin. \par
\tab\ldblquote Counter-petitions?\rdblquote  Little Miss asked. \ldblquote And what does that mean?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote It means that there is going to be intervention on the opposing side,\rdblquote  Stanley Feingold told her. Stanley was the head of the firm now--old John was in semi-retirement--and he was handling Andrew\rquote s case personally. He looked so much like his father, down to the rounded belly and the amiable smile, that he could almost have been John\rquote s younger twin. But he did not affect green-tinted contact lenses. \par
\tab\ldblquote Intervention by whom?\rdblquote  Little Miss demanded. \par
\tab Stanley took a deep breath. \ldblquote The Regional Labor Federation, for one. They\rquote re worried about losing jobs to robots if robots are given their freedom.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s ancient history. The world doesn\rquote t have enough human workers to fill all the available jobs as it is, and everybody knows it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Nevertheless, the labor people will always jump in to prevent any kind of innovation that might further the concept of robot rights. If robots become free entities, they might be able to claim job seniority--union membership--all kinds of things of that sort.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Ridiculous.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, I know, Mrs. Charney. But they are filing a petition of intervention, all the same. And they are not the only ones who are.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Who else?\rdblquote  said Little Miss in an ominous voice. \par
\tab\ldblquote The United States Robots and Mechanical Men Corporation,\rdblquote  Feingold said. \par
\tab\ldblquote They \i are?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i0\ldblquote Is it so surprising? They are the world\rquote s sole manufacturers of robots, Mrs. Charney. Robots are their main product. Their product, let it be said, with some stress on that word--and products are inanimate things. The U.S.R.M.M. people are disturbed at the idea that anyone might come to consider robots to be anything more than that. If Andrew\rquote s petition succeeds in gaining freedom for robots, U.S.R.M.M. probably fears, then it may succeed in gaining other rights for them as well--civil rights, \i human \i0 rights. So of course they will want to fight against that. Just as a manufacturer of shovels and pick-axes regards its products as mere inanimate tools, not as persons, Mrs. Charney, and would be likely to oppose any legal ruling that gave its shovels and pick-axes any sort of civil rights which might lead the shovels and pick-axes to attempt to control the way they are manufactured, warehoused, and sold.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Nonsense. Absolute nonsense!\rdblquote  Little Miss cried, with a ferocity in her tone that was worthy of Sir. \par
\tab\ldblquote I agree,\rdblquote  Stanley Feingold said diplomatically. \ldblquote But the interventions have been filed, all the same. And there are others besides these two. We also find ourselves faced with objections from--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Never mind,\rdblquote  said Little Miss. \ldblquote I don\rquote t want to hear the rest of the list. Just go in there and refute every single stupid argument that these reactionaries put forth.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You know I\rquote ll do my best, Mrs. Charney,\rdblquote  Feingold said. \par
\tab But there wasn\rquote t a great deal of confidence in the lawyer\rquote s tone. \par
\tab The next development came just a week before the trial. Little Miss called Feingold and said, \ldblquote Stanley, we\rquote ve just received notice that television crews will be coming to my father\rquote s house on Monday to set up the special wiring for the hearing.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, of course, Mrs. Charney. It\rquote s quite routine.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Is the hearing going to be held at my father\rquote s house?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Andrew\rquote s deposition will be taken there, yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And the rest of the trial?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It isn\rquote t a trial, exactly, Mrs. Charney.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The rest of the proceedings, then. Where will they take place? In Judge Kramer\rquote s courtroom?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The usual procedure,\rdblquote  Feingold said, \ldblquote is for each concerned party involved in the action to participate electronically. The judge will receive all the inputs in his chambers.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No one goes to court in person any more?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Rarely, Mrs. Charney. Very rarely.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But it does still happen?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote As I said, very rarely. The world is so decentralized now, people have spread out over such great distances--it\rquote s so much easier to do these things electronically.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I want this done in a courtroom.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Feingold gave her a quizzical look. \ldblquote Is there any special reason why--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. I want the judge to be able to see Andrew face to face, to listen to his actual voice, to form a close-range opinion of his character. I don\rquote t want him to think of Andrew as some sort of impersonal machine whose voice and image are coming to him over telephone lines. Besides which, I very much don\rquote t want my father to have to put up with the stress and turmoil of technical crews invading his privacy to wire his house for whatever kind of transmission is necessary.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Feingold nodded. He looked troubled. \ldblquote In order to assure a courtroom hearing at this late date, Mrs. Charney, I would have to file a writ of--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote File it, then.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The intervening parties will certainly object to the extra expense and inconvenience involved.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Let them stay home from the hearings, then. I wouldn\rquote t want them put to the slightest inconvenience, not for all the world. But Andrew and I intend to be in that courtroom.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Andrew and \i you, \i0 Mrs. Charney?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Did you think I was going to stay home that day?\rdblquote  \par
\tab And so it came to pass that the appropriate writ was filed, and the intervening parties grumbled but could raise no sustainable objection--for it was still anyone\rquote s right to have his day in court, electronic testimony being by no means mandatory--and on the appointed day Andrew and Little Miss at last presented themselves at the surprisingly modest chambers of Judge Kramer of the Fourth Circuit of the Regional Court for the long-awaited hearing on the petition that was, for purely technical reasons, listed on the docket as Martin vs. Martin. \par
\tab Stanley Feingold accompanied them. The courtroom--located in a tired-looking old building that might have gone back to Twentieth Century times--was surprisingly small and unglamorous, a modest little room with a plain desk at one end for the judge, a few uncomfortable chairs for those rare people who insisted on appearing in person, and an alcove that contained the electronic playback devices. \par
\tab The only other human beings present were Judge Kramer himself--unexpectedly youthful, dark-haired, with quick glinting eyes--and a lawyer named James Van Buren, who represented all the intervening parties gathered into a single class. The various intervening parties themselves were not present. Their interventions would be shown on the screen. There was nothing they could do to overturn the writ Feingold had secured, but they had no desire to make the trip to court themselves. Almost no one ever did. So they had waived their right to be physically present in the courtroom and had filed the usual electronic briefs. \par
\tab The positions of the intervenors were set forth first. There were no surprises in them. \par
\tab The spokesman for the Regional Labor Federation did not place much explicit stress on the prospect for greater competition between humans and robots for jobs, if Andrew were granted his freedom. He took a broader, loftier way of raising the issue: \par
\tab\ldblquote Throughout all of history, since the first ape-like men chipped the edges of pebbles into the chisels and scrapers and hammers that were the first tools, we have realized that we are a species whose destiny it is to control our environment and to enhance our control of it through mechanical means. But gradually, as the complexity and capability of our tools have increased, we have surrendered much of our own independence--have become dependent on our own tools, that is, in a way that has weakened our power to cope with circumstances without them. And now, finally, we have invented a tool so capable, so adept at so many functions, that it seems to have an almost human intelligence. I speak of the robot, of course. Certainly we admire the ingenuity of our roboticists, we applaud the astonishing versatility of their products. But today we are confronted with a new and frightening possibility, which is that we have actually created our own successors, that we have built a machine that does not know it is a machine, that demands to be recognized as an autonomous individual with the rights and privileges of a human beingand which, by virtue of its inherent mechanical superiority, its physical durability and strength, its cunningly designed positronic brain, its bodily near-immortality, might indeed, once it has attained those rights and privileges, begin to regard itself as our master! How ironic! To have built a tool so good that it takes command of its builders! To be supplanted by our own machinery--to be made obsolete by it, to be relegated to the scrapheap of evolution--\rdblquote  \par
\tab And so on and on, one resonant clich\'e9 after another. \par
\tab\ldblquote The Frankenstein complex allover again,\rdblquote  Little Miss murmured in disgust. \ldblquote The Golem paranoia. The whole set of ignorant anti-science anti-machine anti-progress terrors dragged forth one more time.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Still, even she had to admit that it was an eloquent statement of the position. As Andrew sat watching the screen, listening to the lawyer for the Labor Federation pour forth his stream of horrors, he found himself wondering why anyone thought robots would \i want \i0 to supplant human beings or to relegate them to any sort of scrapheap. \par
\tab Robots were here to serve. It was their purpose. It was their pleasure, one might almost say. But even Andrew found himself wondering whether, as robots grew to be more and more like human beings, it might become so difficult to tell the one from the other that the humans, lacking the built-in perfection of robots, would indeed come to look upon themselves as a second-rate kind of creature. \par
\tab Eventually the tirade of the Labor Federation\rquote s spokesman ended. The screen dimmed and a brief recess was called. Then it was the turn of the speaker from United States Robots and Mechanical Men. \par
\tab Her name was Ethel Adams. She was a sharp-featured, taut-faced woman of middle years, who--probably not by any coincidence--bore a striking resemblance to the celebrated robopsychologist Susan Calvin, that great and widely revered scientific figure of the previous century. \par
\tab She did not indulge in any of the previous speaker\rquote s inflated rhetoric. She said simply and predictably that to grant Andrew\rquote s position would greatly complicate the ability of U.S.R.M.M. to design and manufacture the robots that were its main product--that if the company could be shown to be producing not machines but free citizens, it might be liable to all sorts of bewildering new restrictions that would critically hamper its work--that, in short, the whole course of scientific progress would be placed in needless jeopardy. \par
\tab It was, of course, the direct opposite of the first speaker\rquote s position. He had held up the advance of technology as something worthy of dread; she was warning that it might be placed in serious danger. But the contradiction was only to be expected, Stanley Feingold said to Little Miss and Andrew. The real weapons that were being used in today\rquote s struggle were emotions, not serious intellectual concepts. \par
\tab But there was one more speaker: Van Buren, the attorney who was there in person as the general representative of all those who had taken issue with Andrew\rquote s request. He was tall and impressive, with classic senatorial mien: the close-cropped graying hair, the costly suit, the magnificently upright posture. And he had an extremely simple argument to offer, one that did not in any way attempt to deal with emotional issues: \par
\tab\ldblquote What it comes down to, your honor, is an issue so basic--so trivial, even--that I am not really sure why we are all here today. The petitioner, Robot NDR-113, has requested of his owner, the Honorable Gerald Martin, that he be declared \lquote free.\rquote  A free robot, yes, the first of his kind. But I ask you, your honor: what meaning can this possibly have? A robot is only a machine. Can an automobile be \lquote free\rquote ? Can an electronic screen be \lquote free\rquote ? These questions have no answers because they have no content. Human beings can be free, yes. We know what that means. They have, as one of our great ancestors wrote, certain inalienable rights to life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness. Does a robot have life? Not as we understand it. It has the \i semblance \i0 of life, yes--but so does the image on the face of a holocube. Nobody would argue that holocube images need to be set \lquote free.\rquote  Does a robot have liberty? Not as we understand the word: they are so far from having liberty that their very brains are constructed in such a way that they must obey human commands. And as for the pursuit of happiness--what can a robot possibly know about that? Happiness is a purely human goal. Freedom is a purely human state. A robot--a mere mechanical thing built out of metal and plastic, and from the very start of its existence intended and designed entirely as a device to serve the needs of human beings--is by definition not an object to which the concept of \lquote freedom\rquote  can be applied. Only a human being is capable of being free.\rdblquote  \par
\tab It was a good speech, clear and direct and expertly delivered. Van Buren was obviously aware of the excellence of the points he was making, because he went on to make them several more times in various forms, speaking slowly and with great precision, his hand coming down rhythmically on the desk before him to mark the cadence of his words. \par
\tab When he was done, the judge called another recess. \par
\tab Little Miss turned to Stanley Feingold and said, \ldblquote It\rquote ll be your turn next, right?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. Of course.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I want to speak first. On Andrew\rquote s behalf.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Feingold turned red. \ldblquote But, Mrs. Charney--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I know you\rquote ve got a wonderful brief ready to deliver. I\rquote m not in any way trying to imply that you don\rquote t. But the judge has heard enough oratory today. I want to go up there and make a very simple statement, and I want to do it before anyone else has a chance to make a speech. Even you, Stanley.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Feingold was obviously displeased. But he knew who his client was. Andrew might be paying the bills, but Little Miss was running the show. \par
\tab He made the necessary request. \par
\tab Judge Kramer frowned, shrugged, nodded. \par
\tab\ldblquote Very well,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote  Amanda Laura Martin Charney may approach the bench.\rdblquote  \par
\tab For a moment Andrew, sitting quietly beside Feingold, wondered who that might be. He had never heard Little Miss referred to by her full name before. But then he saw the lean, trim figure of Little Miss rise and move forcefully toward the front of the room, and he understood. \par
\tab Andrew felt sudden hot currents of excitement running through his pathways at the sight of Little Miss standing so boldly there before the judge. How fearless she seemed! How determined! How--beautiful! \par
\tab She said, \ldblquote Thank you, your honor. I am not a lawyer and I don\rquote t really know the proper legal way of phrasing things. But I hope you\rquote ll listen to my meaning and not be troubled if I don\rquote t use the right kind of Latin terms.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That will not be a problem, Mrs. Charney.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Little Miss smiled faintly and said, \ldblquote I\rquote m extremely grateful for that, your honor. --We have come here today because NDR-113, as the speakers on the other side so impersonally choose to refer to him, has petitioned to be declared a free robot. I should tell you that it sounds very strange to me to hear my dear friend Andrew referred to as NDR-113, although I am aware, more or less, that that was his serial number when he came to us from the factory long ago. I was only six or seven years old then, and so, as you can see, that was quite a considerable time back. I found NDR-113 an unpleasant thing to call him, and so I gave him the name of \lquote Andrew.\rquote  And because he has been with our family, and only our family, throughout all the intervening years, he is known generally as \lquote Andrew Martin.\rquote  With your permission, your honor, I would like to continue to refer to him as Andrew.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The judge nodded almost indifferently. It was not a real issue: the petition had been filed in the name of Andrew Martin in the first place. \par
\tab Little Miss continued, \ldblquote I spoke of him as my friend. That is what he is. But he is other things as well. He is also our family servant. He is a robot. It would be absurd to deny that that is what he is. And--despite the eloquent speeches we\rquote ve heard today--I think I need to make it clear that all he\rquote s asking of the court is to be declared a free \i robot. \i0 Not, as they would have us think, to be declared a free man. He\rquote s not here today looking to gain the right to vote, or to marry, or to have the Three Laws removed from his brain, or anything else like that. Humans are humans and robots are robots and Andrew knows perfectly well which side of the line he belongs on.\rdblquote  \par
\tab She paused then and looked glintingly across the room at James Van Buren as though expecting him to nod in agreement. But Van Buren offered no response other than a cool, bland professional stare. \par
\tab Little Miss went on, \ldblquote Very well. The issue, then, is freedom for Andrew, and nothing else. \par
\tab\ldblquote Now, Mr. Van Buren has argued that freedom is a meaningless concept when it is applied to robots. I beg to disagree, your honor. I disagree most strongly. \par
\tab\ldblquote Let\rquote s try to understand what freedom means to Andrew, if that is possible. In some ways, he \i is \i0 free already. I think it must be at least twenty years since anyone in the Martin family has given Andrew an order to do something that we felt he might not do of his own accord. In part that has been a matter of common courtesy: we like Andrew, we respect him, in some ways it is fair to say that we \i love \i0 him. We would not do him the unkindness of allowing him to think that we feel it necessary to give him orders of that kind, when he has lived with us so long that he\rquote s perfectly capable of anticipating what needs to be done and doing it without having to be told. \par
\tab\ldblquote But we could, if we wish, give him any sort of order at any time, and couch it as harshly as we wish, because he is a machine that belongs to us. That is what it says on the papers that came with him, on that day so long ago when my father first introduced him to us: he is our robot, and by virtue of the second of the famous Three Laws he is absolutely bound to obey us when we give him a command. He has no more ability to reject the option of obedience to human beings than any other kind of machine. And I tell you, your honor, that it troubles us deeply that we should have such power over our beloved Andrew. \par
\tab\ldblquote Why should we be in a position to treat him so callously? What right do we have to hold such authority over him? Andrew has served us for decades, faithfully, uncomplainingly, lovingly. He has made the life of our family happier in a thousand ways. And quite apart from his devoted and unquestioning service to us, he has--completely on his own initiative --mastered the craft of woodworking to such a degree that he has produced, over the years, an astonishing series of remarkably beautiful pieces that can only be termed works of art, and which are eagerly sought after by museums and collectors everywhere. Considering all of that, how can we continue to be able to exert such power over him? By what right are we enabled to set ourselves up as the absolute masters of such an extraordinary person?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i\ldblquote A person, \i0 Mrs. Charney?\rdblquote  Judge Kramer interjected. \par
\tab Little Miss looked momentarily discomforted. \ldblquote  As I said at the beginning, your honor, I lay no claim to Andrew\rquote s being anything but a robot. Certainly I accept the reality of that. But I have known him so long, and so closely, that to me he is like a person. Let me amend what I said a moment before, then. By what right, I should say, are we enabled to set ourselves up as the absolute masters of such an extraordinary robot?\rdblquote  \par
\tab The judge frowned. \ldblquote So the purpose of this petition--am I correct, Mrs. Charney?--is to have the Three Laws removed from Andrew\rquote s brain in order that he be no longer subject to human control?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all,\rdblquote  replied Little Miss, sounding shocked. The question had taken her completely off guard. \ldblquote I\rquote m not even sure that such a thing would be possible. And look--look: even Andrew is shaking his head. There you are. It \i isn\rquote t \i0 possible. And it certainly never has been what we had in mind when the petition was filed.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Then just what \i did \i0 you have in mind, may I ask?\rdblquote  the judge said. \par
\tab\ldblquote Only this. That Andrew be awarded a legally binding document which says that he is a free robot who owns himself, that if he chooses to continue serving the Martin family, it is by his own choice and not because we elect to exercise the rights vested in us by our original contract with his manufacturers. It\rquote s a purely semantic issue, really. Nothing involving the Three Laws would be changed--even if it could be. We are simply trying to invalidate the condition of involuntary servitude in which we are compelled to keep Andrew now. After which he, on his part, would continue to serve us just as he does now--of that I\rquote m quite sure. But he would do it entirely because he wanted to, which I believe that he does, and not because we require him to. Don\rquote t you see, your honor, how much that would mean to him? It would give him everything and cost us nothing. And none of the immense and tragic problems of the overthrow of humanity by its own machines that the Labor Federation speaker so dramatically alluded to would enter into the case in the slightest way, I assure you.\rdblquote  \par
\tab For a moment the judge seemed to be suppressing a smile. \ldblquote I think I see your point, Mrs. Charney. I appreciate the warmth and passion with which you\rquote ve spoken as your robot\rquote s advocate. --You are aware, are you not, that there\rquote s really nothing in the law codes of this Region or of any other that deals with the question of whether robots can be free in the sense that you propose? There\rquote s simply no body of precedent at all.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  Little Miss said. \ldblquote Mr. Feingold has made that quite clear to me already. But every departure from established precedent has to begin somewhere, after all.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote So it does. And I could make a ruling that would establish new law here. It would be subject to reversal in a higher court, naturally, but it would be within my powers to give my assent to the petition as it is now constituted, and thus to make your robot \lquote free\rquote  in the sense of a waiver by the Martin family of its inherent right to give him orders. For whatever that would be worth to him and to you, I could do that. But I need, first, to come to grips with the point that Mr. Van Buren has raised: the unspoken assumption in our society that only a human being can enjoy freedom, virtually by definition of the word. Judges who run counter to fundamental assumptions of that kind--who make rulings that sound impressive but are inherently meaningless--tend to be regarded as fools. Obviously I don\rquote t want to turn this court into a laughing-stock. And therefore there are still some aspects of this case that I need to understand more clearly.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote If there\rquote s anything else you want to ask me, your honor--\rdblquote  Little Miss said. \par
\tab\ldblquote Not you. Andrew. Let the robot come forward.\rdblquote  Little Miss gasped. She looked toward Stanley Feingold and saw him sit up suddenly with a look of excitement on his face for the first time since she had told him that she intended to pre-empt his turn to address the court. \par
\tab As for Andrew, he had risen and was striding toward the front of the room with an air of the greatest dignity and nobility about him. He was completely calm--not only externally, where he had no way of displaying visible emotion anyway, but within. \par
\tab Judge Kramer said, \ldblquote For the record: you are Robot NDR-113, but you prefer to be known as Andrew, is that correct?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, your honor.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The timbre of Andrew\rquote s voice had come through the series of successive updatings to sound entirely human by this time. Little Miss had grown quite accustomed to that, but the judge seemed astonished, as though he had expected some sort of clanking grinding metallic tone to emerge. So it was a moment before the proceedings continued. \par
\tab Then the judge said, peering at Andrew with intense interest, \ldblquote Tell me one thing, Andrew, if you will. \i Why \i0 do you want to be free? In what way will this matter to you?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew replied, \ldblquote Would you wish to be a slave, your honor?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Is that how you see yourself? A slave?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Little Miss--Mrs. Charney--used the term \lquote involuntary servitude\rquote  to describe my condition. That is exactly what it is. I must obey. I \i must. \i0 I have no choice. That is nothing other than slavery, your honor.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Even if I pronounced you free this minute, Andrew, you would still be subject to the Three Laws.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I understand that completely. But I would not be subject to Sir and Little Miss--to Mr. Martin and Mrs. Charney. I could, at any time, leave the household where I have lived for many years and take up residence anywhere else I chose. They would have waived their right to order me back into service. Thus I would cease to be a slave.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Is that what you want, Andrew? To leave the Martin house and go somewhere else?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not in the least. All I want is the right to choose to do so, if I should feel the desire.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The judge studied Andrew carefully. \ldblquote You have referred to yourself several times as a slave--the slave of these people who obviously have such great affection for you and whose service, you tell us, you have no wish to leave. But you are not a slave. A slave is one whose freedom has been taken away from him. You never were free, and had no freedom to lose: you were created for the explicit purpose of serving. A robot, a mechanical adjunct to human life. You are a perfectly good robot--a genius of a robot, I am given to understand--capable of a degree of artistic expression that few or perhaps no other robots have ever attained. Since you don\rquote t want to leave the Martins, and they don\rquote t seem to want you to leave, and your life among them has apparently been that of a cherished member of the family, this all seems like something of a tempest in a teapot, Andrew. What more could you accomplish if you were free?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Perhaps no more than I do now, your honor. But I would do it with greater joy. It has been said in this courtroom today that only a human being can be free. But I think that is wrong. It seems to me that only someone who wishes for freedom--who knows that there is such a concept, and desires it with all his will--is entitled to freedom. I am such a one. I am not human, not by any means. Never have I asserted that I am. But I wish for freedom, all the same.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew\rquote s voice died away. He held his place before the bench, utterly motionless. \par
\tab The judge sat nearly as rigidly, staring down at him. He appeared to be lost in thought. Everyone in the room was totally still. \par
\tab It seemed an eternity before the judge spoke. \par
\tab Then at last he said, \ldblquote The essential point that has been raised here today, I think, is that there is no right to deny freedom to any--\i object--\i0 that possesses a mind sufficiently advanced to grasp the concept and desire the state. It is a point well taken, I think. I have heard the statements from all sides and I have reached my preliminary conclusions. I intend to rule in favor of the petitioner.\rdblquote  \par
\tab His formal decision, when it was announced and published not long afterward, caused a brief but intense sensation throughout the world. For a little while hardly anyone talked of anything else. A free robot? How could a robot be free? What did it mean? Who was this strange robot, anyway, who seemed so far in advance of the rest of his kind? \par
\tab But then the hubbub over the Andrew Martin case died down. It had been only a nine days\rquote  wonder. Nothing had really changed, after all, except insofar as Andrew\rquote s relationship to the Martin family was concerned. \par
\tab The intervenors against Andrew\rquote s petition appealed to the World Court. In time the case made its way upward. The members of the Court listened carefully to the transcript of the original hearing and found no grounds for reversal. \par
\tab So it was done, and Andrew had had his wish fulfilled. He was free, now. It was a wonderful thing to contemplate. And yet he sensed, somehow, that he had not quite achieved whatever it was that he had set out to achieve when he first approached Sir to ask to be freed. \par
