SIR REMAINED DISPLEASED. He could find no reason to rejoice in the court\rquote s decision and made sure that Andrew and Little Miss knew it. \par
\tab Andrew came to him soon after the decree was final and said, \ldblquote I have the check for you, Sir.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What check are you talking about?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote For the entire balance in my corporate account. Which I promised to pay over to you, Sir, as the price for giving me my freedom.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I never gave you your freedom!\rdblquote  Sir retorted. \ldblquote You simply went and took it!\rdblquote  His harsh voice made Andrew feel almost as though he were being short-circuited. \par
\tab\ldblquote Father--\rdblquote  Little Miss said, sternly. \par
\tab Sir, who was sitting huddled in his armchair with his lap-robe wrapped about him even though this was the warmest day of the summer so far, scowled at her. But in a somewhat more conciliatory tone he said, \ldblquote  All right, Andrew. You wanted your freedom, for whatever that may be worth to you, and I didn\rquote t object to it. I suppose that must be interpreted as meaning that I supported your petition. Well, then, consider that I did. So now you are free. You have my congratulations, Andrew.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And I want to make the payment that I promised.\rdblquote  Sir\rquote s eyes flashed with a trace of their old fire. \ldblquote I don\rquote t want your damned money, Andrew!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote We had an agreement, Sir--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Agreement? What agreement? You know that I never agreed to anything. --Look, Andrew, I\rquote ll take that check from you if it\rquote s the only way that you\rquote re going to feel that you really are free. But I think the idea\rquote s preposterous. I\rquote m a very wealthy old man and I don\rquote t have very long to live and if you force me to take that money I\rquote m simply going to hand it away to charity. I\rquote ll give it to the Home for Orphaned Robots, if there is one. Or I\rquote ll found one, if there isn\rquote t.\rdblquote  He laughed--a thin, joyless laugh. Neither Andrew nor Little Miss joined in. \ldblquote But you don\rquote t care, do you? You simply want to give the money away. Very well, Andrew. Let me have the check.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Thank you, Sir.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He passed it across to the old man. \par
\tab Sir peered at it for a moment, holding it this way and that until his dimming eyes told him which side of the check he was looking at. \par
\tab\ldblquote You really have accumulated quite a fortune, Andrew. --Give me a pen, will you, Mandy?\rdblquote  Sir\rquote s hand shook as he took it from her, but when he began to write on the back of the check it was in bold, steady strokes that went on for line after line, an inscription much longer than a mere endorsement would have required. He studied what he had written and nodded. Then he handed the check back to Andrew. \par
\tab Sir had endorsed the check \i Gerald Martin, received as payment in full for the freedom of Robot Andrew NDR-113\i0  \i Martin, per court decision. \i0 And then beneath that he had drawn a line and written, \i Pay to the order of Andrew Martin, as bonus for outstanding services rendered during the period of his employment here. His endorsement of this check implies irrevocable acceptance of the bonus. Gerald Martin. \par
\tab\i0\ldblquote Will that be acceptable, Andrew?\rdblquote  Sir asked. \par
\tab Andrew hesitated a moment. He showed the check to Little Miss, who read what Sir had written and shrugged. \par
\tab\ldblquote You leave me with no choice, Sir,\rdblquote  Andrew said. \par
\tab\ldblquote Precisely. That\rquote s the way I like things to be. Now fold that check up and put it in your pocket--no, you don\rquote t have a pocket, do you?--well, put it away \i somewhere. \i0 Keep it as a souvenir, something to remember me by. And let\rquote s hear nothing more about it.\rdblquote  Sir glared defiantly at both Andrew and Little Miss. \ldblquote So. That\rquote s done, then. And now you\rquote re properly and truly free, is that right? Very well. Very well. From now on you can select your own jobs around this place and do them as you please. I will give you no orders ever again, Andrew, except for this final one: that you do only what you please. As of this moment you must act only according to your own free will, as stipulated and approved by the courts. Is that clear?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But I am still responsible for you. That too, as stipulated and approved by the courts. I don\rquote t own you any more, but if you happen to get yourself into any trouble, I\rquote m the one who will have to get you out of it. You may be free but you don\rquote t have any of the civil rights of a human being. You remain my dependent, in other words--my ward, by court order. I hope you understand that, Andrew.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Little Miss said, \ldblquote You sound angry, Father.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I am. I didn\rquote t ask to have responsibility for the world\rquote s only free robot dumped on me.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Nothing has been dumped on you, Father. You accepted responsibility for Andrew the day you arranged to take him into your home. The court order doesn\rquote t change a bit of that. You won\rquote t have to do anything that you weren\rquote t bound to do before. As for Andrew\rquote s getting himself into trouble, what reason do you think he will? The Three Laws still hold.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Then how can he be considered free?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew said quietly, \ldblquote  Are not human beings bound by their laws, Sir?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Sir glowered. \ldblquote Don\rquote t chop logic with me, Andrew. Human beings have voluntarily arrived at a social contract, a code of laws which they willingly agree to abide by because life in a civilized society would be untenable otherwise. Those who refuse to abide by those laws, and therefore make life untenable for others, are punished and, we like to think, eventually rehabilitated. But a robot doesn\rquote t live by any voluntary social contract. A robot obeys its code of laws because it has no choice but to obey. Even a so-called free robot.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But as you say, Sir, human laws exist and must be obeyed, and those who live under those laws regard themselves as free nevertheless. So a robot--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Enough!\rdblquote  Sir roared. He swept his lap-robe to the floor and lurched uncertainly out of his chair. \ldblquote I don\rquote t feel like discussing this any further, thank you. I\rquote m going upstairs. Good night, Amanda. Good night, Andrew.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Good night to you, Sir. Shall I see you to your room?\rdblquote  Andrew asked. \par
\tab\ldblquote You needn\rquote t bother. I\rquote m still strong enough to climb a flight of stairs. You go about your business, whatever that may be, and I\rquote ll go about mine.\rdblquote  \par
\tab He tottered away. Andrew and Little Miss exchanged troubled glances, but neither of them said anything. \par
\tab After that Sir rarely left his bedroom. His meals were prepared and brought to him by the simple TZ-model robot who looked after the kitchen. He never asked Andrew upstairs for any reason, and Andrew would not take it upon himself to intrude on Sir\rquote s privacy; and so from that time on Andrew saw Sir only on those infrequent occasions when the old man chose to descend into the main part of the house. \par
\tab Andrew had not lived in the house himself for some time. As his woodworking business had expanded, it had become awkward for him to continue to operate out of the little attic studio that Sir had set aside for him at the beginning. So it had been decided, a few years back, that he would be allowed to set up a little dwelling of his own, a two-story cabin at the edge of the woods that flanked the Martin estate. \par
\tab It was a pleasant, airy cabin, set on a little rise, with ferns and glistening-leaved shrubs all about, and a towering redwood tree just a short distance away. Three robot workmen had built it for him in a matter of a few days, working under the direction of a human foreman. \par
\tab The cabin had no bedroom, of course, nor a kitchen, nor any bathroom facilities. One of the rooms was a library and office where Andrew kept his reference books and sketches and business records, and the other and much larger room was the workshop, where Andrew kept his carpentry equipment and stored the work in progress. A small shed adjoining the building was used to house the assortment of exotic woods that Andrew used in the jewelry-making segment of his enterprise, and the stack of less rare lumber that went into his much-sought-after pieces of furniture. \par
\tab There was never any end of jobs for him to do. The publicity over his attaining free status had generated worldwide interest in the things that Andrew made, and scarcely a morning went by without three or four orders turning up on his computer. He had a backlog of commissions stretching years into the future, now, so that he finally had to set up a waiting list simply for the privilege of placing an order with him. \par
\tab He was working harder now as a free robot than he ever had in the years when he had technically been the property of Sir. It was not at all unusual for Andrew to put in thirty-six or even forty-eight straight hours of work without emerging from his cabin, since he had no need, naturally, for food or sleep or rest of any kind. \par
\tab His bank account swelled and swelled. He insisted on repaying Sir for the entire cost of building his little house, and this time Sir was willing to accept the money, purely for the sake of proper form. Title to the structure was legally transferred to Andrew and he executed a formal lease covering the portion of Gerald Martin\rquote s land on which the building stood. \par
\tab Little Miss, who still lived just up the coast in the house she and Lloyd Charney had built long ago when they had first been married, never failed to look in on him whenever she came to Sir\rquote s estate to pay a call on her father. As a rule Little Miss would stop off at Andrew\rquote s workshop as soon as she arrived, and chat with him awhile and look at his latest projects, before going on into the main house where Sir was. \par
\tab Often she brought Little Sir with her--though Andrew no longer called him that. For Little Sir had ceased to be a boy quite some time back--he was a tall and robust young man now, with a flaring russet-colored mustache nearly as awesome as his grandfather\rquote s and an imposing set of side-whiskers as well, and soon after the court decision that made Andrew a free robot he forbade Andrew to use the old nickname. \par
\tab\ldblquote Does it displease you, Little Sir?\rdblquote  Andrew asked. \ldblquote I thought you found it amusing.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I did.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But now that you are a full-grown man, it seems condescending to you, is that it? An affront to your dignity? You know I have the highest respect for your--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It has nothing to do with my dignity,\rdblquote  Little Sir said. \ldblquote It has to do with yours.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t understand, Little Sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Evidently not. But look at it this way, Andrew: \lquote Little Sir\rquote  may be a charming name, and you and I certainly take it that way, but in fact what it is is the kind of groveling name that an old family retainer would use when speaking to the master\rquote s son, or in this case the master\rquote s grandson. It isn\rquote t appropriate any more, do you see, Andrew? My grandfather isn\rquote t your master nowadays, and I\rquote m not a cute little boy. A free robot shouldn\rquote t call anyone \lquote Little Sir.\rquote  Is that clear? I call you Andrew--always have. And from now on you must call me George.\rdblquote  \par
\tab It was phrased as an order, so Andrew had no choice but to agree. \par
\tab He ceased calling George Charney \ldblquote Little Sir\rdblquote  as of that moment. But Little Miss remained Little Miss for him. It was unthinkable for Andrew to have to call her \ldblquote Mrs. Charney\rdblquote  and even \ldblquote Amanda\rdblquote  seemed like an improper and impertinent mode of address. She was \ldblquote Little Miss\rdblquote  to him and nothing other than \ldblquote Little Miss,\rdblquote  even though she was a woman with graying hair now, lean and trim and as beautiful as ever but undeniably growing old. Andrew hoped that she would never give him the same sort of order that her son had; and she never did. \ldblquote Little Miss\rdblquote  it was; \ldblquote Little Miss\rdblquote  it would always be. \par
\tab One day George and Little Miss came to the house, but neither of them made the usual stop at Andrew\rquote s place before going in to see Sir. Andrew noticed the car arrive and continue on past his own separate little driveway, and wondered why. He felt troubled when half an hour passed, and then half an hour more, and neither of them came to him. Had he given offense in some way on their last visit? No, that seemed unlikely. \par
\tab But was there some problem in the main house, then? \par
\tab He distracted himself by plunging into his work, but it took all his robotic powers of self-discipline to make himself concentrate, and even so nothing seemed to go as smoothly as it usually did. And then, late in the afternoon, George Charney came out back to see him--alone. \par
\tab\ldblquote Is anything wrong, George?\rdblquote  Andrew asked, a moment after George had entered. \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m afraid that there is, Andrew. My grandfather is dying.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Dying?\rdblquote  Andrew said numbly. \par
\tab Death was a concept he had long thought about, but had never really understood. \par
\tab George nodded somberly. \ldblquote My mother is at his bedside now. Grandfather wants you to be there too.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote He does? It isn\rquote t your mother who has sent for me, but Sir himself?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Sir himself, yes.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew felt a faint tremor in his fingertips. It was as close as he could come to a physical expression of excitement. But there was distress mingled with the sensation. \par
\tab Sir--dying! \par
\tab He shut down his tools and hurried across to the main house, with George Charney trotting along beside him. \par
\tab Sir was lying quietly in the bed in which he had spent most of his time in recent years. His hair had thinned to a few white wisps; even his glorious mustache now was a sad drooping thing. He looked very pale, as though his skin were becoming transparent, and he scarcely seemed to be breathing. But his eyes were open--his fierce old eyes, his piercing, intense blue eyes--and he managed a small smile, the merest upturning of his lips, as he saw Andrew come into the room. \par
\tab\ldblquote Sir--oh, Sir, Sir--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Come here, Andrew.\rdblquote  Sir\rquote s voice sounded surprisingly strong: the voice of the Sir of old. \par
\tab Andrew faltered, too confused to respond. \par
\tab\ldblquote Come here, I said. That\rquote s an order. I said once that I wasn\rquote t going to give you any more orders, but this is an exception. Just about the last one I\rquote m ever going to give you--you can count on that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, Sir. \ldblquote  Andrew came forward. \par
\tab Sir pulled one hand out from under the coverlet. It seemed to be something of a struggle for him to move the blanket aside, and George rushed forward to help him. \par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  Sir said, with a trace of his familiar irascibility. \ldblquote Damn it, don\rquote t try to do it for me, George! I\rquote m only dying, not crippled.\rdblquote  Angrily he pushed the coverlet down just far enough to raise his hand, and held it out toward the robot. \ldblquote Andrew,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Andrew--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Oh, Sir,\rdblquote  Andrew began. \par
\tab And he fell silent. He did not know what to say. \par
\tab He had never before been at the side of someone who was dying, had never so much as seen a dead person. He knew that death was the human way of ceasing to function. It was an involuntary and irreversible dismantling that happened eventually to all human beings. Since it was inevitable, Andrew wanted to think that it was something that humans took for granted as a natural process and did not look upon with fear or distaste. But he was not entirely sure of that. And Sir had lived so long--he must be so \i accustomed \i0 to being alive, and there had always been so much life and vitality in him--\par
\tab\ldblquote Give me your hand, Andrew.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Of course, Sir.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew took Sir\rquote s cool, pale, shriveled hand into his own: gnarled ancient flesh against smooth ageless plastic that was without flaw. \par
\tab Sir said, \ldblquote You\rquote re a splendid robot, do you know that, Andrew? Truly splendid. The finest robot that was ever made.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Thank you, Sir.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I wanted to tell you that. And one other thing. I\rquote m glad you\rquote re free. That\rquote s all. It\rquote s important to me that I had a chance to tell you that. All right, Andrew.\rdblquote  \par
\tab It was an unmistakable dismissal. Andrew no longer had Sir\rquote s attention. He released Sir\rquote s trembling hand and stepped back from the bed, taking up a position alongside George and Little Miss. Little Miss reached forward and touched Andrew\rquote s arm just above the elbow, lightly, affectionately. But she said nothing. Nor did George. \par
\tab The old man seemed to have withdrawn into some private realm, far away. The only sound in the room now was Sir\rquote s increasingly rough breathing, becoming ever more harsh, ever less regular. Sir lay motionless, staring upward at nothing at all. His face was as expressionless as any robot\rquote s. \par
\tab Andrew was utterly at a loss. He could only remain standing, absolutely silent, absolutely motionless, watching what he knew must be Sir\rquote s final moments. \par
\tab The old man\rquote s breathing grew rougher yet. He made an odd gargling sound, deep in his throat, that was like no sound Andrew had ever heard in his entire existence. \par
\tab Then all was still. Other than the cessation of Sir\rquote s breathing, Andrew was unable to detect any change in him. He had been virtually motionless a moment ago and he was motionless now. He had stared blindly upward before and he was staring upward now. Andrew realized, though, that something profound had just happened, something that was wholly beyond his comprehension. Sir had passed across that mysterious threshold that separated death from life. There was no more Sir. Sir was gone. Only this empty husk remained. \par
\tab Little Miss broke the endless silence at last with a soft cough. There were no tears in her eyes, but Andrew could see that she was deeply moved. \par
\tab She said, \ldblquote I\rquote m glad you got here before he went, Andrew. You belonged here. You were one of us.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Once more Andrew did not know what to reply. \par
\tab Little Miss said, \ldblquote  And it was wonderful to hear him say what he did to you. He may not have seemed friendly to you toward the end, Andrew, but he was old, you know. And it hurt him that you should have wanted to be free. But he forgave you for that right at the last, didn\rquote t he, Andrew?\rdblquote  \par
\tab And then Andrew found the words to say. He said, \ldblquote I never would have been free without him, Little Miss.\rdblquote  \par
\par
