\f0 IT WAS ONLY AFTER Sir\rquote s death that Andrew started to wear clothes. He began with an old pair of trousers at first, a pair that he had obtained from George Charney. \par
\tab It was a daring experiment, and he knew it. Robots, being metallic in exterior cladding and sexless in design--despite the \ldblquote he\rdblquote  or \ldblquote she\rdblquote  designations that their owners tended to hang on them--had no need for clothing, neither as protection against the elements nor as any sort of shield for modesty. And no robot, so far as Andrew knew, had ever worn any. \par
\tab But some curious longing within Andrew seemed to have arisen lately that led him to want to cover his body in the way humans did, and--without pausing to examine the motivation that was leading him toward it--he set out to do so. \par
\tab The day Andrew acquired the trousers, George had been with him in his workshop, helping him stain some porch furniture for his own house. Not that Andrew needed the help--indeed, it would have been very much simpler all around if George had let him do it by himself--but George had insisted on participating in the job. It was furniture for his own porch, after all. He was the man of the house--George was married now, and a lawyer with the old Feingold firm, which for the past few months had been caned Feingold and Charney, with Stanley Feingold as the senior partner--and he took his adult responsibilities very, very seriously. \par
\tab At the end of the day the furniture was stained and so, quite thoroughly, was George. He had splotches of stain on his hands, on his ears, on the tip of his nose. His russet mustache and ever more flamboyant side-whiskers were stained too. And, of course, there was stain allover his clothing. But at least George had come prepared for that, bringing an expendable shirt to work in and a disreputable-looking pair of trousers that he must have had since his high school days. \par
\tab As he was changing back into his regular clothes when the job was done, George crumpled up the old shirt and trousers and said, as he tossed them aside, \ldblquote You might as well just throw these things in the trash, Andrew. They\rquote re of no use to me any more.\rdblquote  \par
\tab George was right about the shirt. Not only was it badly stained, but it had split right down the seam from the arm to the shirt-tail when George reached out too far too quickly while trying to turn a porch table on its side. But the trousers, frayed and worn as they were, seemed salvageable to Andrew. \par
\tab He held them up with their legs dangling. \ldblquote If you don\rquote t mind,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote I\rquote d like to keep these for myself.\rdblquote  \par
\tab George grinned. \ldblquote To use as rags, you mean?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew paused just a moment before replying. \par
\tab\ldblquote To wear,\rdblquote  he said. \par
\tab Now it was George\rquote s turn to pause. Andrew could see the surprise on his face, and then the amusement. George was trying hard not to smile, and he was more or less succeeding at it, but the effort was all too obvious to Andrew\rquote s eyes. \par
\tab\ldblquote To--wear,\rdblquote  George said slowly. \ldblquote You want to wear my old pants. Is that what you just said, Andrew?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It is. I would very much like to wear them, if that is all right with you.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Is something going wrong with your homeostatic system, Andrew?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all. Why do you ask?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Only that I was wondering if you were feeling chilly these days. Why else would you want to wear those pants?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote To find out what it is like.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Ah,\rdblquote  George said. And then after a bit he said, again, \ldblquote  Ah. I see. You want to find out what it\rquote s like. All right, I can tell you, Andrew. What it will feel like is like having a dirty old piece of rough unpleasant cloth wrapped around your fine smooth metal skin.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Are you saying that you don\rquote t want me to put the trousers on?\rdblquote  Andrew asked. \par
\tab\ldblquote I didn\rquote t say that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But you think it\rquote s a peculiar idea.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Well--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You do.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. As a matter of fact, I do. Very damned peculiar indeed, Andrew.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And therefore you refuse to give me the trousers except for the purpose of destroying them?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  George said. There was a note of exasperation in his voice. \ldblquote Do whatever you want with them, Andrew. Try them on, if you like. Why should I have any objections? You\rquote re a free robot. You can put on a pair of pants if that\rquote s what you feel like doing. I don\rquote t see any reason at all why I should stand in your way. --Go on, Andrew. Put them on.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Andrew. \ldblquote Yes, I will.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It\rquote s a moment for the history books. The first time a robot has put on clothes. I ought to get my camera, Andrew.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew brought the trousers close to his waist. But then he hesitated. \par
\tab\ldblquote Well?\rdblquote  George asked. \par
\tab\ldblquote Will you show me how to do it?\rdblquote  Andrew said. \par
\tab Grinning broadly now, George showed Andrew how to manipulate the static charge so as to allow the trousers to open, wrap about his lower body, and move shut. George demonstrated the technique a couple of times with his own trousers, but Andrew was quite aware that it was going to take him a while to duplicate that one flowing motion, which George, after all, had been performing since he was a child. \par
\tab\ldblquote It is the twist of the wrist when you bring the hand upward that puzzles me,\rdblquote  Andrew said. \par
\tab\ldblquote Like this,\rdblquote  said George, and did it yet again. \par
\tab\ldblquote Like that?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote More like this.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Like this, yes.\rdblquote  Andrew touched the little stud once again and the trousers opened, fell, rose, and closed themselves about his legs. \ldblquote Right?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Much better,\rdblquote  said George. \par
\tab\ldblquote A little practice and it will seem natural to me, I think,\rdblquote  Andrew said. \par
\tab George gave him an odd look. \ldblquote No, Andrew. It\rquote s never going to seem natural to you. Because it \i isn\rquote t \i0 natural. --Why on Earth do you want to wear trousers, Andrew?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote As I said before, George. Out of curiosity about what it is like to be clothed.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But you weren\rquote t naked before you put them on. You were simply--yourself.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes, I suppose I was,\rdblquote  Andrew said noncommittally. \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m trying to be sympathetic. But for the life of me I still can\rquote t understand what you\rquote re up to, Andrew. Your body is so beautifully functional that it\rquote s a downright shame to cover it--especially when you don\rquote t need to worry about either temperature control or modesty. And the fabric doesn\rquote t really cling properly, not on metal.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew said, \ldblquote Are not human bodies beautifully functional, George? Yet you all cover yourselves.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote For warmth, for cleanliness, for protection, for decorativeness. And as a concession to social custom. None of that applies to you.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew said, \ldblquote I feel bare without clothes.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You do? You\rquote ve never said a word about that before today, so far as I know. Is this something new?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Reasonably new.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote A week? A month? A year? --What\rquote s going on, Andrew?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It is hard for me to explain. I have begun to feel\i --different. \i0\ldblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Different! Different from whom? It isn\rquote t as though a robot is any novelty any more. Andrew, there are millions of robots on Earth now. In this Region, according to the last census, there are almost as many robots as there are humans.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I know that, George. There are robots doing every conceivable kind of work.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And not a single one of them wears clothes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But none of them is free, George.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote So that\rquote s it! You feel different because you \i are \i0 different!\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Exactly.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But to wear clothes--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Indulge me, George. I want to do this.\rdblquote  \par
\tab George let out his breath in a long, slow exhalation. \par
\tab\ldblquote Whatever you say. You\rquote re a free robot, Andrew.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. I am.\rdblquote  \par
\tab After his initial skepticism George seemed to find Andrew\rquote s venture into wearing clothes curious and amusing. He cooperated by bringing him, little by little, new additions to his wardrobe. Andrew could hardly go into town to purchase clothing himself, and he felt ill at ease even about ordering it from the computer catalogs, because he knew that his name was widely known in many places ever since the court decision, and he didn\rquote t want some shipping clerk in a storeroom far away to recognize it on an order form and begin spreading the word that the free robot was now going in for wearing clothing. \par
\tab So George would supply him with the articles he requested: a shirt first, then shoes, a fine pair of gloves, a set of decorative epaulets. \par
\tab\ldblquote What about underwear?\rdblquote  George asked. \ldblquote Should I get you some of that too?\rdblquote  But Andrew had no idea of the existence or purpose of underwear, and George had to explain it to him. Andrew decided that he had no need of it. \par
\tab He tended to wear his new clothes only when he was alone at home. He was hardly ready to go outdoors in them; and even in his own cabin he stopped wearing them in the presence of others after a few preliminary experiments. He was inhibited by George\rquote s patronizing smile, which with the best will in the world George continued to be unable to conceal, and by the bewildered stares of the first few customers who saw him dressed when they came to him to commission work. \par
\tab Andrew might be free, but there was built into him a carefully detailed program concerning his behavior toward human beings: a neural channel that was not as powerful in its effect as the Three Laws, but nevertheless was there to discourage him from giving any sort of offense. It was only by the tiniest steps that he dared advance. Open disapproval would set him back months. It was an enormous leap for him when he finally allowed himself to leave his house with clothing on. \par
\tab No one he encountered that day showed any sign of surprise. But perhaps they were too astounded even to react. And indeed even Andrew himself still felt strange about his experiment with clothing. \par
\tab He had a mirror, now, and he would study himself for long periods of time, turning from side to side, looking at himself from all angles. And sometimes he found himself reacting with disfavor to his own appearance. His metal face, with its glowing photoelectric eyes and its rigidly carved robotic features, sometimes struck Andrew himself as strikingly incongruous now that it rose up out of the soft, brightly colored fabrics of clothing meant for a human body. \par
\tab But at other times it seemed to him perfectly appropriate for him to be wearing clothing. Like virtually all robots, he had been designed, after all, to be fundamentally humanoid in shape: two arms, two legs, an oval head set upon a narrow neck. The U. S. Robots designers had not needed to give him that form. They could have made him look any way they deemed efficient--with rotors instead of legs, with six arms instead of two, with a swiveling sensor-dome atop his trunk instead of a head with two eyes. But no: they had patterned him after themselves. The decision had been made, very early in the history of robotics, that the best way to overcome mankind\rquote s deep-seated fear of intelligent machines was to make them as familiar in form as possible. \par
\tab In that case, why should he not wear clothing also? That would make him look even more human, wouldn\rquote t it? \par
\tab And in any event Andrew \i wanted \i0 to wear clothing now. It seemed symbolic to him of his new status as a legally free robot. \par
\tab Of course, not everyone accepted Andrew as free, regardless of what the legal finding had been. The term \ldblquote free robot\rdblquote  had no meaning to many people: it was like saying \ldblquote dry water\rdblquote  or \ldblquote bright darkness.\rdblquote  Andrew was inherently incapable of resenting that, and yet he felt a difficulty in his thinking process--a slowing, an inner resistance--whenever he was faced with someone\rquote s refusal to allow him the status he had won in court. \par
\tab When he wore clothing in public, he knew, he risked antagonizing such people. Andrew tried to be cautious about that, therefore. \par
\tab Nor was it only potentially hostile strangers who had difficulty with the idea of his wearing clothing. Even the person who most loved him in all the world--Little Miss--was startled and, Andrew suspected, more than a little troubled by it. Andrew saw that from the very first time. Like her son George, Little Miss had tried to conceal her feelings of surprise and dismay at the sight of Andrew in clothing. And, like George, she had failed. \par
\tab Well, Little Miss was old now and, like many old people, she had grown set in her ways. Maybe she simply preferred him to look the way he had looked when she was a girl. Or, perhaps, she might believe on some deep level that robots--all robots, even Andrew--should look like the machines that they were, and therefore should not dress like people. \par
\tab Andrew suspected that if he ever should question Little Miss on that point she would deny it, probably quite indignantly. But he had no intention of doing that. He simply tended to avoid putting on clothes--or too many of them--whenever Little Miss came to visit him. \par
\tab Which was none too often, these days, for Little Miss was past seventy now--well past seventy--and had grown very thin and sensitive to cold, and even the mild climate of Northern California was too cool for her most of the year. Her husband had died several years before, and since then Little Miss had begun spending much of her time traveling in the tropical parts of the world--Hawaii, Australia, Egypt, the warmer zones of South America, places like that. She would return to California only occasionally, perhaps once or twice a year, to see George and his family --and, of course, Andrew. \par
\tab After one of her visits George came down to the cabin to speak with Andrew and said ruefully, \ldblquote Well, she\rquote s finally got me, Andrew. I\rquote m going to be running for the Legislature next year. She won\rquote t give me any peace unless I do. And I\rquote m sure you know that the First Law of our family, and the Second Law and the Third Law as well, is that nobody says \lquote no\rquote  to Amanda Charney. So there I am: a candidate. It\rquote s my genetic destiny, according to her. Like grandfather, like grandson, is what she says.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Like grandfather--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew stopped, uncertain. \par
\tab\ldblquote What is it, Andrew?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Something about the phrase. The idiom. My grammatical circuit--\rdblquote  He shook his head. \i\ldblquote Like \i0 grandfather, \i like \i0 grandson. There\rquote s no verb in the statement, but I know how to adjust for that. Still--\rdblquote  \par
\tab George began to laugh. \ldblquote What a literal-minded hunk of tin you can be sometimes, Andrew\rdblquote\lquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Tin?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Never mind about that. What the other expression meant was simply that I, George, the grandson, am expected to do what Sir, the grandfather, did--that is to say, to run for the Regional Legislature and have a long and distinguished career. The usual expression is, \lquote Like father, like son,\rquote  but in this case my father didn\rquote t care to go into politics, and so my mother has changed the old clich\'e9 so that it says--Are you following all this, Andrew, or am I just wasting my breath?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I understand now.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Good. But of course the thing my mother doesn\rquote t take into account is that I\rquote m not really all that much like my grandfather in temperament, and perhaps I\rquote m not as clever as he was, either, because he had a truly formidable intellect, and so there\rquote s no necessary reason why I\rquote d automatically equal the record he ran up in the Legislature. There\rquote ll never be anyone like him again, I\rquote m afraid.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew nodded. \ldblquote  And how sad for us that he is no longer with is. I would find it pleasant, George, if Sir were still--\rdblquote  He paused, for he did not want to say, \ldblquote in working order.\rdblquote  He knew that that would not be the appropriate expression to use. And yet it was the first phrase that had come into his mind. \par
\tab\ldblquote Still alive?\rdblquote  George finished for him. \ldblquote Yes. Yes, it would be good to have him around. I have to confess I miss the old monster at least as much as you do.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Monster?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote In a manner of speaking.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Ah. Yes. A manner of speaking.\rdblquote  \par
\tab When George had gone, Andrew replayed the conversation in his mind, puzzling over its twists and turns and trying to see why he had been so badly off balance throughout it. It had been George\rquote s use of idiomatic phrases and colloquial language, Andrew decided, that had caused the problems. \par
\tab Even after all this time, it was still difficult sometimes for Andrew to keep pace with humans when they struck out along linguistic pathways that were something other than the most direct ones. He had come into being equipped with an extensive innate vocabulary, a set of grammatical instructions, and the ability to arrange words in intelligible combinations. And through whatever fluke in his generalized positronic pathways it was that made Andrew\rquote s intelligence more flexible and adaptable than that of the standard robot, he had been able to develop the knack of conversing easily and gracefully with humans. But there were limits to his abilities along that line. \par
\tab The problem was only going to get worse as time went along, Andrew realized. \par
\tab Human languages, he knew, were constantly in a state of flux. There was nothing fixed or really systematic about them. New words were invented all the time, old words would change their meanings, all sorts of short-lived informal expressions slipped into ordinary conversation. That much he had already had ample reason to learn, though he had not done any kind of scientific investigation of the kinds of changes that tended to take place. \par
\tab The English language, which was the one Andrew used most often, had altered tremendously over the past six hundred years. Now and then he had looked at some of Sir\rquote s books, the works of the ancient poets--Chaucer, Spenser, Shakespeare--and he had seen that their pages were sprinkled with footnotes to explain archaic word usage to modern readers. \par
\tab What if the language were to change just as significantly in the \i next \i0 six hundred years? How was he going to be able to communicate with the human beings around him, unless he kept up with the changes? \par
\tab Already, in one brief conversation, George had baffled him three times. \ldblquote Like grandfather, like grandson.\rdblquote  How simple that seemed now that George had explained it--but how mysterious it had been at first. \par
\tab And why had George called him a \ldblquote hunk of tin,\rdblquote  when George surely knew that there was no tin in Andrew\rquote s makeup whatsoever? And--it was the most puzzling one of all--why should George have called Sir a \ldblquote monster,\rdblquote  when that was plainly not an appropriate description of the old man? \par
\tab Those were not even the latest modern phrases, Andrew knew. They were simply individual turns of phrase, a little too colloquial or metaphorical for instant handling by Andrew\rquote s linguistic circuitry. He would face far more mystifying ways of speech in the outside world, he suspected. \par
\tab Perhaps it was time for him to update some of his linguistic documentation. \par
\tab His own books would give him no guidance. They were old and most of them dealt with woodworking, with art, with furniture design. There were none on language, none on the ways of human beings. Nor was Sir\rquote s library, extensive as it was, likely to be of much use. No one was living in the big house just now--it was sealed, under robot maintenance--but Andrew still could have access to it whenever he wanted. Nearly all of Sir\rquote s books, though, dated from the previous century or before. There was nothing there that would serve Andrew\rquote s purpose. \par
\tab All things considered, the best move seemed to be for him to get some up-to-date information--and not from George. When Andrew turned to George at the time he had wanted to start wearing clothing, he had had to fight his way through George\rquote s incomprehension and a certain amount of George\rquote s condescending amusement. Though he doubted that George would treat him the same way in this matter, he preferred not to find out. \par
\tab No, he would simply go to town and use the public library. That was the proper self-reliant thing to do--the correct way for a free robot to handle a problem, he told himself. It was a triumphant decision and Andrew felt his electropotential grow distinctly higher as he contemplated it, until he had to throw in an impedance coil to bring himself back to equilibrium. \par
\tab To the library, yes. \par
\tab And he would dress for the occasion. Yes. Yes. Humans did not enter the public library unclothed. Neither would he. \par
\tab He put on a full costume--elegant leggings of a velvety purple fabric, and a flowing red blouse with a satiny sheen, and his best walking boots. He even donned a shoulder chain of polished wooden links, one of his finest productions. It was a choice between that and another chain he had, one made of glitter-plastic, which perhaps was better suited for daytime wear; but George had said that the wooden chain was terribly impressive, particularly since anything made of wood was far more valuable than mere plastic. And he wanted to impress, today. There would be humans in the library, not robots. They would never have seen a robot there before. It was important for him to look his best. \par
\tab But he knew that he was doing something unusual and that there might be unusual consequences. If George dropped by unexpectedly, he would be surprised to find Andrew gone, and he might be troubled by that. \par
\tab Andrew had placed a hundred feet between himself and the house before he felt resistance gathering within himself and rapidly reaching the level that would bring him to a halt. He shifted the impedance coil out of circuit, and when that did not seem to make much difference, he returned to his home and on a piece of paper wrote neatly: \par
\par
\pard\qc I HAVE GONE TO THE LIBRARY.\par
--Andrew Martin\par
\pard\par
and placed it in clear view on his worktable. \par
