\f0 THE APPOINTMENT wasn\rquote t easy to arrange, even using Paul\rquote s supposedly powerful name. \par
\tab But repeated pressure--coupled with the none too delicate hint that permitting Andrew to have a few minutes of Harley Smythe-Robertson\rquote s precious time might well save U. S. Robots and Mechanical Men from having to go through a troublesome new round of litigation over robot rights--finally carried the day. On a balmy spring day Andrew and Paul set out together across the country for the vast and sprawling complex of buildings that was the headquarters of the gigantic robotics company. \par
\tab Harley Smythe-Robertson--who was descended from both branches of the family that had founded U. S. Robots, and had adopted the hyphenated name by way of declaring that fact--looked remarkably unhappy at the sight of Andrew. He was approaching retirement age and an extraordinary amount of his tenure as president of the company had been devoted to the controversies over robot rights. Smythe-Robertson was a tall, almost skeletally lean man whose gray hair was plastered thinly over the top of his scalp. He wore no facial makeup. From time to time during the meeting he eyed Andrew with brief but undisguised hostility\par
\tab\ldblquote And what new trouble have you come here to cause us, may I ask?\rdblquote  Smythe-Robertson said. \par
\tab\ldblquote Please understand, sir, it has never been my intention to cause this company trouble. Never.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But you have. Constantly.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I have only attempted to gain that to which I have felt entitled.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Smythe-Robertson reacted to the word \ldblquote entitled\rdblquote  as he might have to a slap in the face. \par
\tab\ldblquote How extraordinary to hear a robot speak of feelings of entitlement. \ldblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote This robot is a very extraordinary robot, Mr. Smythe-Robertson,\rdblquote  said Paul. \par
\tab\ldblquote Extraordinary,\rdblquote  Smythe-Robertson said sourly. \ldblquote Yes. Quite extraordinary.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew said, \ldblquote Sir, slightly more than a century ago I was told by Melwin Mansky, who was the Chief Robopsychologist of this company then, that the mathematics governing the plotting of the positronic pathways was far too complicated to permit of any but approximate solutions, and that therefore the limits of my own capacities were not fully predictable.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote As you say, that was over a century ago,\rdblquote  Smythe-Robertson replied. And after a moment\rquote s hesitation added icily, \i\ldblquote Sir. \i0 The situation is quite different nowadays. Our robots are made with great precision now and are trained precisely to their tasks. We have eliminated every aspect of unpredictability from their natures.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Paul. \ldblquote So I\rquote ve noticed. And one result is that my receptionist has to be guided at every point that departs from the expected path, however slightly. I don\rquote t see that as much of a step forward in the state of the art.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Smythe-Robertson said, \ldblquote I think you\rquote d like it a great deal less if your receptionist were to improvise.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Improvise?\rdblquote  Paul said. \i\ldblquote Think \i0 is all I ask. Enough thinking to be able to handle the simple situations a receptionist needs to deal with. Robots are designed to be intelligent, aren\rquote t they? It seems to me you\rquote ve backtracked toward a very limited definition of intelligence indeed.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Smythe-Robertson fidgeted and glowered, but made no direct response. \par
\tab Andrew said, \ldblquote Are you saying, sir, that you no longer manufacture any robots that are as flexible and adaptable as--let us say--myself?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s right. We discontinued the generalized-pathways line so long ago that I couldn\rquote t tell you how far back it was. Perhaps it was in Dr. Mansky\rquote s time. Which was long before I was born, and as you see, I am far from young.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote As am I,\rdblquote  said Andrew. \ldblquote The research I have done in connection with my book--I think you know that I have written a book about robotics and robots--indicates that I am the oldest robot presently in active operation.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Correct,\rdblquote  said Smythe-Robertson. \ldblquote And the oldest ever. The oldest that will ever be, in fact. No robot is useful after its twenty-fifth year. Their owners are entitled to bring them in at that time and have them replaced with new models. In the case of leased robots, we call them in automatically and provide the replacements.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote No robot \i in any of your presently manufactured series \i0 is useful after the twenty-fifth year,\rdblquote  said Paul pleasantly. \ldblquote But Andrew is a robot of a quite different sort.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Indeed he is,\rdblquote  said Smythe-Robertson. \ldblquote I\rquote m only too aware of that.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew, adhering steadfastly to the path he had marked out for himself, said, \ldblquote Since I am the oldest robot in the world and the most flexible one in existence, would you not say that I am so unusual that I merit special treatment from the company?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all,\rdblquote  said Smythe-Robertson icily. \ldblquote Let me be blunt with you--\i sir. \i0 Your unusualness is a continuing embarrassment to the company. You have caused us all manner of difficulties, as I\rquote ve already pointed out, as a result of the various activist positions you have taken over the years. Your feelings of--ah--\i entitlement \i0 are not shared here. If you were on lease as most of our robots are, instead of having been acquired by outright purchase through some regrettable bit of ancient administrative carelessness, we\rquote d have called you in long ago and replaced you with a robot of a more docile type.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote At least you\rquote re straightforward about it,\rdblquote  Paul said. \par
\tab\ldblquote There\rquote s no secret about the way we feel over this. We\rquote re in business to sell robots, not to engage in endless unprofitable political squabblings. A robot that believes it\rquote s something more than a useful mechanical device is a direct threat to our corporate welfare.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And therefore you would destroy me if you could,\rdblquote  said Andrew. \ldblquote I quite understand that. But I am a free robot and I own myself, so I can\rquote t be called in and it would be pointless to make an attempt to repurchase me. And I am protected by the law against any harm you might want to do to me. Which is why I have been willing to put myself in your hands for periodic upgrading. And why I have come to you today to request the most extensive upgrading you have ever done on any robot. What I want is a total replacement for myself, Mr. Smythe-Robertson.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Smythe-Robertson looked both astounded and bewildered. He stared at Andrew in total silence, and the silence went on for a seemingly interminable time. \par
\tab Andrew waited. He looked past Smythe-Robertson toward the wall, where a holographic portrait looked back at him. It showed a dour, austere female face: the face of Susan Calvin, the patron saint of all roboticists. She had been dead nearly two centuries now, but after having delved into her working papers as deeply as he had during the course of writing his book, Andrew felt he knew her so well that he could half persuade himself that he had met her in life. \par
\tab Smythe-Robertson said finally, \ldblquote A total replacement, you say? But what does that \i mean?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\i0\ldblquote Exactly what I said. When you call in an obsolete robot, you provide its owner with a replacement. Well, I want you to provide me with a replacement for me.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Still looking confused, Smythe-Robertson said, \ldblquote But how can we do that? If we replace you, how can we turn the new robot over to you as owner, since in the very act of being replaced you would have to cease to exist?\rdblquote  And he smiled grimly. \par
\tab\ldblquote Perhaps Andrew hasn\rquote t made himself sufficiently clear,\rdblquote  interposed Paul. \ldblquote May I try? --the seat of Andrew\rquote s personality is his positronic brain, which is the one part that cannot be replaced without creating a new robot. The positronic brain, therefore, is the locus of Andrew Martin, who is the owner of the robot in which Andrew Martin\rquote s positronic brain is currently housed. Every other part of the robotic body can be replaced without affecting the Andrew Martin personality--most of those parts, as you may know, have \i already \i0 been replaced, sometimes more than once, in the hundred-odd years since Andrew was first manufactured. Those subsidiary parts are the brain\rquote s possessions. The brain, at its option, can have them replaced at any time, but the continuity of the brain\rquote s existence is unbroken. What Andrew actually wants, Mr. Smythe-Robertson, is simply for you to transfer his brain to a new robotic body.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I see,\rdblquote  Smythe-Robertson said. \ldblquote  A total upgrade, in other words.\rdblquote  But his face showed perplexity again. \ldblquote To what kind of body, may I ask? You already are housed in the most advanced mechanical body that we manufacture.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But you have manufactured androids, haven\rquote t you?\rdblquote  said Andrew. \ldblquote Robots that have the outward appearance of humans, complete to the texture of the skin? That is what I want, Mr. Smythe-Robertson. An android body.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Paul seemed astounded by that. \ldblquote Good Lord,\rdblquote  he blurted. \ldblquote Andrew, I never dreamed that that was what you--\rdblquote  His voice trailed off. \par
\tab Smythe-Robertson stiffened. \ldblquote It\rquote s an absolutely impossible request. Impossible.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Why do you say that?\rdblquote  Andrew asked. \ldblquote I\rquote m willing to pay any reasonable fee, as I have for all the numerous upgrades you\rquote ve given me up to now.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote We don\rquote t manufacture androids,\rdblquote  Smythe-Robertson said flatly. \ldblquote You have, though. I know that you have.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Formerly, yes. The line was discontinued.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Because of technical problems?\rdblquote  Paul asked. \par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all. The experimental android line was quite successful, actually--technically speaking. Their appearance was strikingly human in form, and yet they had all the versatility and ruggedness of robots. We used synthetic carbon-fiber skins and silicone tendons. There was virtually no structural metal involved anywhere--the brain, of course, was still platinum-iridium--and yet they were nearly as tough as conventional metal robots. They were tougher, in fact, weight for weight.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Despite all of which, you never put them on the market?\rdblquote  Paul asked. \par
\tab\ldblquote Correct. We worked up about a dozen experimental models and ran some marketing surveys and decided not to go ahead with the line.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Why was that?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote For one thing,\rdblquote  said Smythe-Robertson, \ldblquote a line of androids would have had to be far more expensive than the standard metal robots--so expensive that we would have had to regard them purely as luxury items, with a potential market so limited in size that it would take many years for us to be able to amortize the expense of setting up a production facility. But that was only a small part of the difficulty. The real problem was negative consumer reaction. The androids looked too human, you see. They reawakened all the ancient fears of making real humans obsolete that had caused us so much trouble two hundred years ago. It made no sense for us to open all that psychotic nonsense up again simply for the sake of setting up a line that was doomed from the outset to be unprofitable anyway.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But the corporation has maintained its expertise in the area of making androids, has it not?\rdblquote  Andrew asked. \par
\tab Smythe-Robertson shrugged. \ldblquote I suppose we still could make them if we saw any sense to it, yes.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You choose not to, though,\rdblquote  said Paul. \ldblquote You\rquote ve got the technology but you simply decline to exercise it. That\rquote s not quite the same thing as what you told us before, that it would be \i impossible \i0 to manufacture an android body for Andrew.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It would be possible, yes--technically. But completely against public policy.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Why? There isn\rquote t any law that I know of against making androids.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Nevertheless,\rdblquote  Smythe-Robertson said, \ldblquote we don\rquote t manufacture them and we don\rquote t intend to. Therefore we are unable to provide the android body that Andrew Martin has requested. And I suggest to you that this conversation has reached a point of no return. If you\rquote ll excuse me, therefore--\rdblquote  And he half rose from his seat. \par
\tab\ldblquote Just a little time longer, if you please,\rdblquote  said Paul in an easy tone that had something more forceful just beneath its surface. He cleared his throat. Smythe-Robertson subsided, looking even more displeased than he had. Paul went on, \ldblquote Mr. Smythe-Robertson, Andrew is a free robot who falls under the protection of the laws that govern robot rights. You are aware of this, of course.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Only too well.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote This robot, as a free robot, freely chooses to wear clothes. This has resulted in his being frequently humiliated by thoughtless human beings, despite the law that supposedly protects robots against such humiliation. It\rquote s quite difficult, you realize, to prosecute vague offenses that don\rquote t meet with the general disapproval of those whose responsibility it is to decide between guilt and innocence.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m not at all surprised to hear that,\rdblquote  said Smythe-Robertson restlessly. \ldblquote U. S. Robots understood that from the start. Your father\rquote s law firm unfortunately did not.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote My father is dead now,\rdblquote  said Paul. \ldblquote But what I see is that we have here a clear offense with a clear target, and we stand ready to take the appropriate action.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What are you talking about?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote My client, Andrew Martin--he has been the client of my firm for many years--is a free robot, by decree of the World Court. That is to say, Andrew is his own owner, and in him, therefore, are vested the legal rights that any human robot owner has in regard to robots in his possession. One of those rights is that of replacement. As you yourself pointed out some time ago during this discussion, the owner of any robot is entitled to ask U. S. Robots and Mechanical Men Corporation for a replacement when his robot reaches the point of obsolescence. In fact, the corporation \i insists \i0 on offering such replacements, and where leased robots are involved will call them in automatically. I\rquote ve stated your policy correctly, is that not so?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well--yes.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Good.\rdblquote  Paul was smiling and thoroughly at his ease. He continued, \ldblquote Now, the positronic brain of my client is the owner of the body of my client--and that body, obviously, is far more than twenty-five years old. By your own definition that body is obsolete and my client is entitled to a replacement.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well--\rdblquote  Smythe-Robertson said again, reddening. His gaunt, almost fleshless face looked like a mask, now. \par
\tab\ldblquote The positronic brain which is my actual client demands the replacement of the robot body in which it is housed, and has offered to pay any reasonable fee for that replacement.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Then let him sign up in the ordinary way and we\rquote ll give him his updating!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote He wants more than an updating. He wants the finest replacement body within your technical capacity, by which he means an android body.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote He can\rquote t have one.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote By refusing,\rdblquote  Paul said smoothly, \ldblquote you condemn him to continued humiliation at the hands of those who, recognizing him as a robot, treat him with contempt because he prefers to wear clothes and otherwise behave in traditionally \lquote human\rquote  fashion.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s not our problem,\rdblquote  said Smythe-Robertson. \par
\tab\ldblquote It becomes your problem when we sue you for refusing to provide my client with a body that would allow him to avoid much of the humiliation he now encounters.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Go ahead and sue, then. Do you think anybody\rquote s going to give a damn about a robot who wants to look human? People will be outraged. He\rquote ll be denounced everywhere for the arrogant upstart that he is.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m not so sure,\rdblquote  Paul said. \ldblquote  Agreed, public opinion wouldn\rquote t ordinarily support the claim of a robot in a lawsuit of that kind. But may I remind you that U. S. Robots is not very popular with the general public, Mr. Smythe-Robertson? Even those who most use robots to their own benefit and profit are suspicious of you. This may be a hangover from the days of anti-robot paranoia: I suspect that\rquote s a good part of it. Or it may be resentment against the immense power and wealth of your company, which has so successfully managed to defend its worldwide monopoly on robot manufacture through a long and clever series of patent maneuvers. Whatever the cause may be, the resentment may exist. If there\rquote s any entity that would be even less popular in such a lawsuit than the robot who wants to look like a human being, it would be the corporation that has filled the world with robots in the first place.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Smythe-Robertson glared. The clenched muscles of his face stood out clearly. He said nothing. \par
\tab Paul went on, \ldblquote In addition, think about what people would say when they find out you\rquote re capable of manufacturing human-looking robots? The lawsuit would very definitely focus a great deal of attention on that very point. Whereas if you quietly and simply provided my client with what he requests--\rdblquote  \par
\tab Smythe-Robertson seemed about to explode. \ldblquote This is coercion, Mr. Charney.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote On the contrary. We\rquote re simply trying to show you where your own best interests lie. A quick and peaceful resolution is all that we\rquote re looking for. Of course, if you compel us to seek legal redress in the courts, that\rquote s a different matter. And then, I think, you will find yourself in an awkward and disagreeable position, particularly since my client is quite wealthy and will live for many centuries to come and will have no reason to refrain from fighting this battle forever.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote We\rquote re not without resources ourselves, Mr. Charney.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m aware of that. But can you withstand an endless legal siege that will expose the deepest secrets of your company? --I put it to you one last time, Mr. Smythe-Robertson. If you prefer to reject my client\rquote s quite reasonable request, you may by all means do so and we\rquote ll leave here without another word being spoken. But we will sue, as is certainly our right, and we will sue most strenuously and publicly, which is bound to create immense difficulties for u. S. Robots, and you will find that you will eventually lose. Are you willing to take that risk?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well--\rdblquote  Smythe-Robertson said, and paused. \par
\tab\ldblquote Good. I see that you\rquote re going to accede,\rdblquote  said Paul. \ldblquote You may still be hesitating now, but you\rquote re going to come around in the end. A very wise decision, may I add. But that leads to a further important point.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Smythe-Robertson\rquote s fury seemed to be fading into sullen glumness. He did not try to speak. \par
\tab Paul continued, \ldblquote Let me assure you that if, in the process of transferring my client\rquote s positronic brain from his present body to the organic one that you ultimately will agree to create for him, there is any damage, however slight, then I will never rest until I have nailed this corporation to the ground.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You can\rquote t expect us to guarantee--\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I can and I will. You\rquote ve had a hundred-odd years of experience in transferring positronic brains from one robot body to another. You can surely use the same techniques in transferring one safely to an android body. And I warn you of this: if one brain-path of my client\rquote s platinum-iridium essence happens to get scrambled in the course of the work, you can be quite certain that I\rquote ll take every possible step to mobilize public opinion against this corporation--that I will expose it before all the world for the criminally vindictive operation that it has plainly revealed itself to be.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Smythe-Robertson said, shifting about miserably in his seat, \ldblquote There\rquote s no way we can provide you with a total waiver of liability. There are risks in any sort of transfer.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Low-probability ones. You don\rquote t lose a lot of positronic brains while you move them from one body to another. We\rquote re willing to accept risks of that sort. It\rquote s the possibility of deliberate and malevolent action against my client that I\rquote m warning you against.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote We wouldn\rquote t be so stupid,\rdblquote  said Smythe-Robertson. \ldblquote  Assuming we go through with this, and I haven\rquote t yet said we would, we\rquote d exert our utmost skills. That\rquote s the way we\rquote ve always worked and the way we intend to continue. You\rquote ve backed me into a corner, Charney, but you\rquote ve still got to realize that we can\rquote t give you a 100% assurance of success. 99%, yes. Not 100.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Good enough. But remember: we\rquote ll throw everything we have at you if we have reason to suspect any sort of intentional harm to our client.\rdblquote  Paul turned to Andrew and said, \ldblquote What do you say, Andrew? Is this acceptable to you?\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew hesitated for nearly a full minute, caught in an equilibrium of First Law potentials. What Paul wanted from him amounted to the approval of lying, of blackmail, of the badgering and humiliation of a human being. \par
\tab But at least no physical harm was involved, he told himself. No physical harm. \par
\tab And he managed at last to come out with a barely audible \ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote  \par
