\f0 IT WAS NOT A DIRECT FIGHT. Andrew had given Simon DeLong the clue to the right strategy to use, and Andrew agreed with the tactic; but it was DeLong\rquote s considered professional opinion that the campaign was going to be roundabout and slow. DeLong counseled patience. \par
\tab\ldblquote I have an endless supply of that, I suppose,\rdblquote  Andrew muttered grimly. \par
\tab Feingold and Charney then entered into a campaign to narrow and restrict the area of combat. \par
\tab A certain Roger Hennessey of San Francisco, who had been the recipient of a Martin prosthetic heart seven years before, had supplied robot janitorial services to the Feingold and Charney offices under a contract that had been in effect since the days of Paul Charney. Abruptly Feingold and Charney stopped paying Hennessey\rquote s bills. The account was a good one and it went back many years, so for a time Hennessey said nothing about it. But when five months of unpaid bills had piled up, Hennessey found an occasion to stop by at Feingold and Charney to have a chat with Simon DeLong. \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m sure you\rquote re not aware of it, Simon, but something seems to have gone wrong with your accounting procedures lately. What I mean is, my invoices have been sitting here open since December, and it\rquote s coming up on June now, and--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. I know.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote --it really isn\rquote t at all like Feingold and Charney to let an account run 80--\rdblquote  Hennessey paused and blinked. \ldblquote What did you say? You \i know, \i0 Simon?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Yes. The account has gone unpaid on my direct instructions, as a matter of fact.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Still blinking in astonishment, Hennessey said, \ldblquote I must be losing my hearing. Or else you\rquote re starting to lose your mind, Simon. Did you actually say you\rquote re deliberately withholding payment?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s right.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote For God\rquote s sake, why?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Because we don\rquote t want to pay you.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote What do you mean, you don\rquote t want to pay me? Do you know how many years my robots have been cleaning these offices, Simon ? Have you ever had the slightest reason in all that time to complain about the quality of the work?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Never. And we intend to retain your services just as before. But we\rquote re not going to pay you any more, Roger.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Hennessey scratched his head and stared. \ldblquote You\rquote ve gone completely around the bend, haven\rquote t you? To sit there with a straight face and tell me a crazy thing like that? You know that what you\rquote re saying is absolute malarkey, so why are you saying it? What\rquote s the matter with you, man? How in the name of God\rquote s green Earth can you speak such insane drivel?\rdblquote  \par
\tab DeLong smiled. \ldblquote There\rquote s quite a good reason for it.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote And what may that be, can I dare to ask?\rdblquote  \par
\tab DeLong said, \ldblquote We aren\rquote t going to pay you because we don\rquote t have to. We\rquote ve decided that your contract with us is invalid, and from now on your robots are going to work for us for nothing if they go on working here at all. That\rquote s the story, Roger. If you don\rquote t like it, sue us.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What? What?\rdblquote  Hennessey cried, sputtering. \ldblquote This gets crazier and crazier. Work for nothing? Back pay withheld? You people are \i lawyers! \i0 How can you let yourself spout such cockeyed nonsense? Contract invalid? For heaven\rquote s sake, why?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Because you\rquote re a robot, Roger. There\rquote s only one robot in the world who has the right to enter into binding contracts, and his name is Andrew Martin. The rest of you, because you are not free robots, have no legal right to enforce\rdblquote  \par
\tab Hennessey turned bright scarlet and rose from his chair. \ldblquote Hold it just a moment, you damned lunatic! Hold it right there! What are you saying? A robot? Me? Now I know you\rquote re out of your mind!\rdblquote  Hennessey ripped open the ornate body-cummerbund he was wearing to reveal his pink, hairy chest. \ldblquote Does this look to you like a robot\rquote s chest, man? Does it? Does it?\rdblquote  Hennessey pinched his own abundant flesh. \ldblquote Is this robot meat, Simon? Damn it, I can\rquote t even begin to understand any of this, but I tell you, if you think you can sit there like that and make a figure of fun out of me for your own perverse pleasure, I\rquote ll sue you people, all right, I\rquote ll sue you black and blue from here to Mars and back, by God, and I\rquote ll see to it that you--\rdblquote  \par
\tab DeLong was laughing. \par
\tab Hennessey halted in mid-flow and said icily, \ldblquote What\rquote s so damned amusing, Simon?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry. I shouldn\rquote t be laughing. I owe you a tremendous apology for letting this go on so long.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I think you do. I don\rquote t expect lawyers to have much of a sense of humor, but a dumb joke like this--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It isn\rquote t a joke, though. We really \i are \i0 going to withhold your fees, Roger. We really \i do \i0 want you to take us to court. Our argument indeed \i is \i0 going to be that you are a robot, and that therefore it is quite within the law for us to thumb our collective nose at our contract with you. And we will defend our position with all the skill at our disposal.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Will you, now?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But it is our profound hope, and our intention as well,\rdblquote  DeLong went on, \ldblquote to lose the suit. And when we do, you\rquote ll not only be paid the back fees that we owe you, which will be placed in escrow for you accruing interest, but we will pay all your legal fees as well, and I can tell you, strictly off the record, that there\rquote ll be a considerable bonus payment for you besides to compensate you for any incidental difficulties that this case may cause you. A \i very \i0 considerable bonus payment.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Hennessey adjusted his cummerbund and took his seat again. He blinked a few more times and shook his head. He peered at DeLong for a time in silence. \par
\tab Then he said quietly, \ldblquote I\rquote m truly sorry for your troubles, Simon. You really have gone completely out of your mind, then. What a great pity that is.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Not at all. I\rquote m as sane as I ever was.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Ah. Are you, do you think?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Absolutely.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote In that case, do you have any objection to telling me what this is all about?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote m afraid it would be improper for us to disclose that to you in advance of the litigation. But I will say, Roger, that we have an excellent reason for it all, which will make sense to you in the fullness of time, and I hope that you\rquote ll cooperate with us even in the dark, so to speak, out of consideration for your long relationship with us. We need you to play along with us, Roger, and we\rquote ll take care of you properly afterward.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Hennessey nodded. He looked a little relieved. \par
\tab\ldblquote So it\rquote s all a maneuver of some sort, then?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote You could call it that, I suppose.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote But you won\rquote t tell me what\rquote s going on?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No. Not now. That would be too much like entering into a conspiracy with you.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote But you \i are \i0 entering into a conspiracy with me!\rdblquote  \par
\tab DeLong grinned. \ldblquote  Are we? All we\rquote re doing is refusing to pay your bill. Bear with us, Roger. You won\rquote t regret it. You have my promise.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Well--\rdblquote  said Hennessey, grudgingly. \par
\tab Hennessey\rquote s bill continued to go unpaid. After three months more Hennessey duly notified Feingold and Charney that he could no longer carry their account. He canceled their service contract and filed suit for back charges. Feingold and Charney arranged for a temporary janitorial service to clean the office, and let the Court know that it was ready to defend its position. \par
\tab When the case of Hennessey vs. Feingold and Charney came to trial, it was one of the junior partners who made the argument in court. He said, simply, that inasmuch as Roger Hennessey could be shown to be a robot rather than a human being Feingold and Charney felt under no obligation to go on honoring its service contract, and had unilaterally abrogated it. \par
\tab The robot Hennessey, the lawyer continued, had gone on sending in his robot janitorial crews for another few months even so, but Feingold and Charney had not asked him to do so and did not believe that payment was necessary, or that Hennessey, as a robot, had any legal right to force them to pay. Robots, the junior partner pointed out, had none of the constitutional protections that human beings enjoyed. In disputes over contracts involving robots, only their owners could sue, not the robots themselves. \par
\tab\ldblquote But my client is \i not \i0 a robot!\rdblquote  Hennessey\rquote s lawyer thundered. \ldblquote It\rquote s as plain as the nose on my client\rquote s face that he\rquote s as human as any of us here!\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Your client,\rdblquote  the Feingold and Charney man replied, \ldblquote was equipped some years ago with a robotic prosthetic heart, is that not the case?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Why--possibly he was. I\rquote d need to check with him on that. But what possible relevance can this--\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote It is quite relevant, I assure you. And I respectfully request the Court to obtain a determination on this point.\rdblquote  \par
\tab The judge looked toward Hennessey. \ldblquote Well, Mr. Hennessey?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote I\rquote ve got a prosthetic ticker, sure. But what--\rdblquote  \par
\tab The Feingold and Charney man said, \ldblquote Our position, your honor, is that the presence of a life-sustaining mechanical artifact of that kind in Mr. Hennessey\rquote s body changes his entire legal status. It is reasonable to argue that he would not be alive today but for the robotic component of his body. We proceed to assert, therefore, that the partly prosthetic Mr. Hennessey is in fact a robot and has been for some years now, and therefore that all contracts into which he may have entered as a human being became null and void when he attained the status of a robot.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote So that\rquote s it!\rdblquote  Hennessey muttered. \ldblquote Well, may I be dipped! The heart makes me a robot, they say? Do they, now? Do they?\rdblquote  And he threw back his head and began to laugh. \par
\tab The uproar in the courtroom was tremendous. The judge pounded his gavel and shouted, but he could scarcely be heard for minutes. Then at last what he was saying came through the furor. The case was dismissed, with a directed verdict in favor of the plaintiff. Mr. Roger Hennesseywhom the Court found to be undeniably human--was entitled to his janitorial fees plus interest plus additional compensation. \par
\tab Feingold and Charney appealed. \par
\tab The case had a more elaborate debate at the appellate level, with expert witnesses called in to discuss definitions of humanity. The issue was approached from every angle--scientific, theological, semantic, philosophic. \par
\tab The verdict in favor of Hennessey was affirmed. \par
\tab Feingold and Charney appealed again. \par
\tab They fought the matter skillfully and tenaciously, losing at every step but always in such a way that the issue widened steadily, from a simple \i Shall Hennessey\rquote s bill be paid? \i0 to, ultimately, \i What is a human being? \i0 At each level they forced the decision to be as broad as possible. \par
\tab It took years, and millions of dollars. Eventually the case reached the jurisdiction of the World Court. \par
\tab Which affirmed the original \i Hennessey \i0 ruling and upheld all the accreted rulings having to do with the valid human status of individuals in whom robotic prostheses had been installed. It is the brain, the World Court declared, that is the highest determinant of humanity. The use of auxiliary devices to sustain the life of the brain can in no way invalidate the fundamental and inalienable humanity of that brain. It is unacceptable, the Court said, to argue that the presence of robotic prostheses within a human being\rquote s body gives that person the status of a robot. \par
\tab When the final decision was handed down, Simon DeLong held what amounted to a victory celebration over the definitive legal defeat. Andrew was, of course, present in the company offices for the great occasion. \par
\tab\ldblquote Well, Andrew, we can feel completely satisfied. We\rquote ve accomplished the two things we set out to do. First of all, we have managed to establish the legal point that no number of prosthetic artifacts in the human body causes it to cease being a human body. Secondly, we have engaged public opinion in the question in such a way as to put it fiercely on the side of a broad and loose interpretation of who is human--since there isn\rquote t a human being in existence, on this world or any other, who doesn\rquote t expect to enjoy a greatly extended life-span as a result of the availability of a wide array of prosthetic devices.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote And do you think the Legislature will now grant me my humanity?\rdblquote  Andrew asked. \par
\tab DeLong looked a little uneasy. \par
\tab\ldblquote Perhaps. Perhaps not.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Is that the best you can offer, after all these years of legal struggle?\rdblquote  \par
\tab DeLong said, \ldblquote I wish that I could be as optimistic as you\rquote d like me to be. But the real battle isn\rquote t won yet. There remains the one organ which the World Court has used as the criterion of humanity.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote The mind.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote The brain, Andrew. That\rquote s what the Court singled out, not the mind. The mind is an abstract concept; the brain is a bodily organ. And human beings have organic cellular brains whereas robots have a platinum-iridium positronic brain if they have one at all--and you certainly have a positronic brain. --No, Andrew, don\rquote t get that look in your eye. I know what you\rquote re thinking. But I\rquote ve been assured that we lack the knowledge to duplicate the functions of a cellular brain in an artificial structure that would be close enough to the organic type to allow it to fall within the Court decision. Not even you could do it.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote What should we do, then?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Make the attempt, of course. Congresswoman Chee will be on our side and so will a growing number of other Legislators. The World Coordinator will undoubtedly go along with whatever a majority of the Legislature decides.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Do we have a majority?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  DeLong said. \ldblquote Far from it. But we might manage to put one together if the public will allow its desire for a broad interpretation of humanity to extend to you. A small chance, I admit. But you are, after all, the man who gave them the prosthetics on which their lives now depend.\rdblquote  \par
\tab Andrew smiled. \ldblquote The \i man, \i0 is that what you said?\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote That\rquote s what I said, yes. Isn\rquote t that what we\rquote ve been fighting for, Andrew?\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote Of course.\rdblquote\par
\tab\ldblquote Then we might as well begin thinking that way here. And carry our thinking onward and outward to the rest of the world until everyone else agrees. It won\rquote t be easy, Andrew. None of this has been, and there\rquote s no reason to think it will get any better. The odds are very much against us, I warn you. But unless you want to give up, we have to take the gamble.\rdblquote  \par
\tab\ldblquote I don\rquote t want to give up,\rdblquote  Andrew said. \par
\par
